<HEADLINE> Yeltsin to Leave for Tokyo After Second Vote on Premier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
has been cleared by his doctors for a 10-hour flight to Tokyo for
an informal summit with his Japanese counterpart.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin's spokesman Sergei Yastrzhembsky said the president's
health was "150 percent" ready for the long-haul journey.
</P>
<P>
The Russian delegation is scheduled to depart for Japan on
Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
The visit, which was originally scheduled for April 11 to 13,
was postponed for a week because of the uncertainty of the Russian
political situation.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin dismissed his entire government on March 23. His
nomination of Sergei Kiriyenko as new prime minister was refused
by the State Duma (lower house of parliament) last Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Duma will hold the second round vote on Kiriyenko on
Friday, shortly before the president leaves for Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
The president and Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto
will discuss space cooperation and put forward other specific
projects throughout the year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
