<HEADLINE> Sensitive Index on BSE Shoots Up by 21.78 Points </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The benchmark index crossed the
900-point level Wednesday on the Bombay Stock Exchange (BSE)
following the sharp upsurge in stock prices on revival of buying
by foreign funds and speculators.
</P>
<P>
Mirroring the mood of the market, the sensitive index shot up
by a whopping 21.78 points, or 2.5 percent to close at 920.31
points.
</P>
<P>
Stock brokers said the sentiment was mainly buoyed by the
government's assurance Tuesday that the process of economic
reforms would be accelerated.
</P>
<P>
The prices were also pushed up by foreign investors who started
buying on Indian bourses following the week-long Easter holiday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. dollar ended sharply higher against the rupee at
39.71/73 and the pound sterling was dearer at 66.84/85 rupees at
the close of the Interbank foreign exchange market.  
</P>
</TEXT>
