<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Dampens Japan's Bid for UNSC Permanent Seat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Italian President Oscar Luigi
Scalfaro has dampened Japan's hopes for a permanent seat on the
United Nations Security Council (UNSC).
</P>
<P>
He told Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto during a
visit to Tokyo that Italy was concerned about a proposal to give
new permanent seats to a limited number of "major" countries.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto had been seeking Italy's understanding on Japan's bid
to become a permanent member of the council, Japanese government
officials said.
</P>
<P>
But the Italian president was quoted as saying: "What we are
worried about is that if the Security Council is limited to some
major powers, so many other countries would be excluded."
</P>
<P>
Scalfaro said Italy had no intention of antagonizing friendly
nations, including Japan, over reforms of the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the Diet (Japan's parliament) earlier Wednesday,
Scalfaro called for enhancing the Italian-Japanese cooperation in
solving global problems such as disarmament and environmental
degradation.
</P>
<P>
Scalfaro arrived here on Monday for a week-long state visit to
Japan. He will leave Tokyo on Thursday for western Japan before
returning home on Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
