<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Exported Arms Worth $260 Million Last </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 15 (Xinhua) -- South Africa exported
military equipment worth over 1.3 billion Rand (260 million U.S.
Dollars) last year, South African Press Association (SAPA) quoted
the country's annual armament export statistics as showing
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
This represented a 34 percent rise in arms sales compared with
the previous year, National Conventional Arms Control Committee
(NCACC) Chairman, Kader Asmal, said in Pretoria Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The bulk of the weapons sold, worth one billion Rand (200
million dollars), was of a lethal nature and fell into the A
category, described as "sensitive major significant equipment",
SAPA said.
</P>
<P>
Material in this category is defined as "conventional
implements of war that could cause heavy personnel casualties and
or major damage and destruction to material, structures, objects
and facilities."
</P>
<P>
India was the biggest buyer of weapons in this class, and
acquired equipment to the value of 572 million Rand (114 million
dollars). Next on the list was Switzerland (19.4 million
dollars), Singapore (16.2 million dollars), and Colombia (11.8
million dollars).
</P>
<P>
In the Middle East, Kuwait imported A category arms totalling
one million dollars, while African clients of such weapons
included the Republic of Congo, Uganda and Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
South Africa suspended arms sales to Rwanda in November 1996
after evidence emerged that Rwandan forces had made cross-border
excursions into former Zaire.
</P>
<P>
In July 1997, the government announced that the sale of
non-lethal arms to Rwanda would resume, adding it would also
consider supplying that country with sensitive weapons.
</P>
<P>
Asmal at the time said the decision was prompted by assurances
from the Rwandan government that the material would not be used
outside its borders.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday he said the government remained committed to
transparency and the disclosure of its arms sales.
</P>
<P>
On arms exports to the Republic of Congo, Asmal said that the
export of arms took place before that country's elected
government was toppled. No requests for exports had been received
since.
</P>
<P>
"And if such a request comes, we will take into account the
fact that the legitimate government was overthrown," said Asmal.
</P>
<P>
South Africa rigorously implemented United Nations arms
embargoes, and was at the bottom of the list of exporters
compared to countries such as the United States, Russia and
Sweden, he said.
</P>
<P>
Countries to which South Africa refused to export arms last
year included Nigeria, Afghanistan, Congo, Burundi, Myanmar,
Sudan, Sri Lanka and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Asmal said no serious claims of arms export breaches had been
levelled against South Africa since the NCACC started its work in
August 1995, and all NCACC decisions were based on
cabinet-approved policy.
</P>
<P>
He said all claims against South Africa of breaches of export
regulations were investigated as soon as possible. But many of
the allegations involved a "bit of destabilization," and were
far-fetched, he said.
</P>
<P>
Asmal said government departments were compiling an inventory
of all weapons in their possession, adding that to date the
figure was remarkable. The list would be tabled before the
cabinet.
</P>
<P>
He said a NCACC document on the future of the defense-related
industry was at an advanced stage. The document was expected to
be adopted at the NCACC's next meeting on April 23, after which
it would be released for public debate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
