<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Aims to Cut 33,000 Civil Service Posts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government said
Wednesday that it is targeting to abolish 33,000 civil service
posts by 2000, with 4,000 jobs expected to go by September this
year.
</P>
<P>
But the time frame of the target is still a matter to be
agreed upon by the Ministry of Finance and the World Bank (WB)
and International Monetary Fund (IMF) over the financing of the
exercise, the Zimbabwe News Agency quoted Dennis Rwafa, public
relations officer of the Public Service Commission, as saying.
</P>
<P>
Rwafa said: "The government intends to abolish 4,000 posts by
September 1998 as part of the public service reform program. At
the end of this second phase of the program (1996-2000) at least
33,000 posts will have been abolished."
</P>
<P>
Most of the civil servants to be retrenched are expected to
take up voluntary retirement.
</P>
<P>
During the first phase of the civil service reform which began
in 1991 and ended in 1996, a total of 23,000 public service posts
were abolished to leave a civil service staff establishment of
184,000.
</P>
<P>
The government, now implementing WB/IMF sponsored economic
reforms, has since 1991 been under pressure to reduce its
expenditure and is even more pressed as it starts on the second
phase of economic restructuring, the Zimbabwe Program for
Economic and Social Transformation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
