<HEADLINE> Ambassador: Dialogue, Cooperation Right Way to Human  Rights Promotion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The right way to promote and
protect human rights is dialogue and cooperation rather than
confrontation, head of the Chinese delegation Wu Jianmin said here
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Delivering a statement on country resolutions at the ongoing
54th session of the Commission on Human Rights, Wu recalled that
since the end of the Cold War in 1992, the human rights commission
has adopted altogether 87 country resolutions, all of which are
directed against developing countries.
</P>
<P>
"This situation is quite abnormal," he said. "What was the
consequence? The atmosphere in this commission became more and
more tense, confrontation more and more intensified, and
politicization more and more serious."
</P>
<P>
"It is the human rights cause and the developing countries that
suffered from it," the Chinese ambassador said. "This situation
should not be allowed to continue."
</P>
<P>
Wu noted that the current session in the first four weeks was
in a better atmosphere than in the past sessions: there have been
more dialogue and cooperation than confrontation.
</P>
<P>
"This shows that people are fed up with confrontation which has
burdened this commission for a long time, and begin to realize
that dialogue and cooperation is the right way to promote and
protect human rights," he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Wu hoped that the spirit of dialogue and cooperation shown in
the past four weeks will be adhered to, for it will only bring
benefit and no harm to all commission members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
