<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Sasol, Chevron to Establish Gas Plant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 15 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's
petrochemical giant, Sasol, has reached an agreement with
multinational Chevron to begin design and engineering activities
leading to the construction of a natural gas-to-liquid fuel plant
in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
South African Press Association (SAPA) Wednesday quoted a
Sasol statement as saying that the undertaking had a projected
capacity of 20,000 barrels a day of high quality, environmentally
superior diesel and naphtha products.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, announced by Sasol's Managing Director and
Chief Executive Officer Pieter Cox, followed encouraging results
from a recently completed commercial and technical evaluation.
</P>
<P>
But SAPA did not say when the agreement was reached.
</P>
<P>
Both companies believe that the cooperation has a bright
future.
</P>
<P>
"Sasol is delighted to join Chevron in this project, and we
are confident that our combined expertise in technology and
hydrocarbon production will support a fruitful association
utilizing the best of both companies," Cox was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Richard Matzke, a Chevron executive, said: "The prospects are
bright for the viability of the plant in Nigeria and looking into
the future, Chevron sees this new partnership as a corner stone
for future projects with Sasol, including the possibility of
expansion of this new technology to other worldwide
applications." 
</P>
</TEXT>
