<HEADLINE> U.S. Considers Pakistan as Important Ally: Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 15 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Ambassador to the United
Nations Bill Richardson said here Wednesday that the U.S.
government considers Pakistan as "our important strategic,
economic and political ally."
</P>
<P>
Talking to reporters on arrival, Richardson said his visit was
just a signal of the importance his country attaches to Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope his talks with Pakistani officials on
Thursday would cover the whole spectrum of their relations and the
issues concerning the region.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's Foreign Office Secretary Shamshad Ahmad, who greeted
Richardson at the Chakalala Airbase near Islamabad, said these
talks would focus on Afghanistan and Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
"We shall have an in-depth exchange of views on the regional
situation with the particular focus on Afghanistan and the Jammu
and Kashmir issue," Shamshad said.
</P>
<P>
Richardson's visit is the second cabinet-level one to Pakistan
by a U.S. official during the tenure of Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif. U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright came here last
November.
</P>
<P>
Richardson is also expected to visit Afghanistan Friday where
he will meet leaders of Afghanistan's warring factions.
</P>
<P>
Observers describe Richardson's visit to India and Pakistan as
part of the "more focus on South Asia" policy declared by the
Clinton administration at the start of its second tenure in
office. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
