<HEADLINE> Clinton Plans to Host Summit on Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 15 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton is
planning to host a summit of African reformers before the end of
his term in Washington as an ambitious series of measures
following his visit to the continent, the Washington Times said on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted a high administration official as saying
that Clinton would like "to change American perceptions on Africa
and to get beyond the images of famine, war and disease."
</P>
<P>
Susan Rice, assistant secretary of state for African affairs,
said the president's objective for the summit is to bring Africa
into a global economy based on open markets and private
initiatives.
</P>
<P>
Clinton first voiced his ambition for an African summit in
Johannesburg last month when he visited South Africa.
</P>
<P>
He told South African business executives that he would invite
the leaders of Africa's "reforming economies," and that the summit
would be followed by regular meetings of finance and economics
ministers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
