<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indo-US Talks Successful: Indian Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The just-concluded Indo-U.S.
talks were "successful and constructive" and were marked by the
common desire to bring about a "qualitatively change in bilateral
relations" between the two countries, a senior Indian official
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In a statement released here Wednesday, Indian Foreign
Secretary K. Raghunath said the two sides discussed regional
security and India's request for transfer of U.S. technology in
the field of nuclear energy.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. delegation led by U.S. permanent representative to the
United Nations bill Richardson left here Wednesday for Pakistan
after two days of talks with Indian officials including Prime
Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee, Home Minister Lal Krishna Advani
and Defense Minister George Fernandes.
</P>
<P>
During the talks described by Indian officials as "in-depth and
wide-ranging," the two sides agreed to work together in the fight
against terrorism and drug trafficking and promoting public
health, population control and environmental issues.
</P>
<P>
Official sources here said the U.S. side acknowledged India's
security concerns.
</P>
<P>
The two countries also decided to continue their discussions
when Indian Foreign Secretary Raghunath resumes the next round of
"strategic dialogue" with U.S. Under Secretary of State Thomas
Pickering in Washington in the first week of May.  
</P>
</TEXT>
