<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lockerbie Lawyer Offers Compromise on Libya-West </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 15 (Xinhua) -- A lawyer for the families of the
British victims of the 1988 explosion of a jetliner over Scotland,
said Wednesday he carried fresh proposals to break the Libya-West
crisis over the trial of two Libya suspects in the air crash.
</P>
<P>
Jim Swire, a spokesman for the defense council of the families
of the British victims in the Pan-Am airliner bombing, told
reporters here the proposals will be sent to Libya by Arab League
(AL) Secretary General Esmat Abdel-Meguid.
</P>
<P>
"We have been able to make certain proposals to him
(Abdel-Meguid) which he has undertaken to pass on to Libya," Swire
said at a news conference following a meeting with the AL chief.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's meeting dealt with the latest developments of the
crisis over the venue of the planned trial of the two Libyans
suspected of blowing up the plane over Lockerbie, Scotland. All
270 passengers on the Pan-Am flight were killed in the incident.
</P>
<P>
Swire did not go into details about the proposals, but made it
clear that London and Washington have not yet accepted them.
</P>
<P>
"The proposals must be satisfactory to Libya, the Security
Council, America and Britain," said Swire who led the British
delegation representing the victims' families here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Swire touched on the April 8th meeting held by the victims'
families committee with British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook,
during which Cook spoke of still-under-wraps "diplomatic
initiatives" to defuse the Libya-West crisis.
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Meguid declined to uncover the proposals or to say
whether they will be acceptable to Libya which wants a trial of
the two suspects either in Libya or in a neutral country.
</P>
<P>
Britain and the U.S. insist the two Libyans be tried in Britain
or the U.S..
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Meguid, however, told the news conference that there is a
"serious dialog that has started and I certainly appreciate it."
</P>
<P>
"I think the decision has to come from our brothers in
Libya... This (the proposals) will be communicated to them, Our
objective is truth and justice and respect of Libya's sovereignty
and dignity," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said there was "an agreement on that" with the British
defense council.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council imposed sanctions on Libya in April
1992 for its refusal to hand over the suspects to the U.S. or
Britain.
</P>
<P>
The Libya-West showdown has been again put under the spotlight
following the International Court of Justice ruling in February,
giving it the jurisdiction over the case.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Britain have watered down the ruling and insisted
that the Security council is the body concerned with the issue.
</P>
<P>
A committee groups representatives of the victims' families,
after a meeting in London last week with Cook, vowed to pursue
pressures on the British government to accept Libya's compromise
solutions to defuse the crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
