<HEADLINE> Lebanese PM to Be in Egypt on Mideast Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Prime Minister Rafiq
Al-Hariri will start a two-day visit next Wednesday to Egypt for
talks with President Hosni Mubarak on the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
Hariri is expected to brief Mubarak on the outcome of the recent
Syrian-Lebanese summit meeting in the Syrian resort Latakia on
Monday and Lebanese drives to pursue the Mideast peace process,
the Middle East News Agency reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian-Lebanese talks will focus on the efforts being
exerted to revitalize the stalled Mideast peace process as well as
the Israeli proposal to withdraw from south Lebanon on condition
that Beirut should provide some security safeguards.
</P>
<P>
Israel decided on April 1 to endorse the U.N. Security Council
Resolution 425, saying that it will pull back its troops from
south Lebanon after negotiating security arrangements with Beirut.
</P>
<P>
Al-Assad and Lebanese President Elias Hrawi insisted that the
withdrawal should be full unconditional. They rejected the Israeli
plan as an attempt to drive a wedge between them and torpedo the
Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
Hariri will also have talks with Egyptian Prime Minister Kamal
el-Ganzouri on means of promoting cooperation in economy and trade.
</P>
<P>
Hariri will further hold a meeting with Arab League Secretary
General Esmat Abdel-Meguid within the framework of the Lebanese
efforts to confront the Israeli political and media campaigns to
sell the idea of conditional implementation of U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Meguid paid a lightning visit last week to Beirut where
he held consultations with Hariri on similar issues.
</P>
<P>
Hariri's visit comes after a surprise visit Wednesday by Syrian
President Hafez Al-Assad to Cairo. The flurry of diplomatic
activity is aimed at coordinating Arab stances on the latest
development on the Lebanese track. 
</P>
