<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ILO: Millions to Lose Jobs Because of Financial  Crisis in Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Millions in the countries worst
affected by the financial crisis in Asia will lose their jobs, the
Geneva-based International Labor Organization (ILO) said in a new
report released here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The workers in the construction, financial services and
manufacturing sectors will suffer more, according to the ILO
report.
</P>
<P>
It said that underemployment will become widespread and the
real earnings of those who can hang on to their jobs will fall
substantially as a result of the decline in labor demand and the
inflation induced by large currency devaluations.
</P>
<P>
Most dramatically, the report predicted, the impressive trends
in poverty reduction achieved in these countries over the past 20
years will be reversed.
</P>
<P>
In the report, ILO called for new policy responses to the
crisis, saying that otherwise, the pain inflicted on Asian
societies will continue to grow in 1998.
</P>
<P>
"This combinations of sharp and unexpected social pain on the
one hand, and lack of collectively provided relief on the other",
ILO warned, "is fertile ground for breeding social unrest".
</P>
<P>
The ILO report, based on the latest available data, focuses
primarily on Indonesia, Thailand and South Korea. It will serve as
a background paper for a high-level meeting of governments, trade
unions and employers organizations in Bangkok on April 22-24.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from China, Indonesia, Malaysia, the
Philippines, South Korea, Singapore, Thailand, Vietnam, and the
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region of China will participate
in the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
