<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EC, EP Jointly Hosts Anti-Corruption Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 15 (Xinhua) -- An anti-corruption conference
concluded here on Wednesday with the participation of businessmen,
scholars, legislators and government officials from the European
Union, EU member states, Canada, Japan, Russia and the United
States.
</P>
<P>
Participants at the two-day conference, entitled "Achieving a
Corruption-Free Commercial Environment", agreed that corruption
hinders international business, limits the possibilities for
business expansion and represents an unnecessary but significant
cost to business.
</P>
<P>
The conference was jointly hosted by the European Commission
and the European Parliament.
</P>
<P>
Anita Gradin, European commissioner responsible for internal
and judicial affairs, said at the conference: "Corruption
undermines the trust of our citizens in our institutions and
markets. It undermines the morality and the ethics which are
necessary for a well-functioning democracy. That is why action is
required at all levels: private, in the member states, in the
union and globally."
</P>
<P>
Commission officials said that the interests of the 15-nation
union are affected directly by corruption as it undermines sound
decision making, damages its financial interests and adversely
affects its external policies.
</P>
<P>
Corruption was also blamed for distorting competition and
challenging the principles of open and free markets and in
particular affecting the proper functioning of the internal
market.
</P>
<P>
Gradin said: "Rules and prohibitions, administrative guidelines
and sanctions alone cannot change the ways of politics or
business. We also have to improve our habits and the way we
think.
</P>
<P>
"In the end, the successful prevention of corruption is
dependent on our ability to raise the level of ethics in our
organizations and in society as a whole."
</P>
<P>
Last year, the European Commission presented to the European
Council of Ministers and the European Parliament a proposal on a
union-wide policy against corruption.
</P>
<P>
The proposal pointed to the need for a coherent union-wide
strategy on corruption both within and outside the union's
borders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
