<HEADLINE> UNHCR Repatriates Ethiopian Refugees in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) Wednesday started repatriation
of Ethiopian refugees in northeastern Kenya for the first phase
of its 1998 repatriation operation.
</P>
<P>
A press release issued here Wednesday said that some 500
refugees in the Dadaab camps will return to Moyale of Ethiopia by
UNHCR-chartered Buffalo aircraft within next week.
</P>
<P>
Over the next months, 400 more Ethiopian refugees will be
repatriated from the Dadaab camps and each returnee will receive
a repatriation grant, funds for transport and a nine-month food
ration from the World Food program.
</P>
<P>
Since 1992, more than 70,000 Ethiopian refugees have returned
home from Kenyan refugee camps and UNHCR has closed 12 camps in
the East African country following their repatriation.
</P>
<P>
In the coming weeks, UNHCR is also expected to repatriate some
1,300 Somali refugees in Jomvu camp in Coast Province, bringing
the total number of repatriated Somali refugees from Kenya to
155,000 in six years.
</P>
<P>
Kenya currently shelters some 179,000 refugees in the Dadaab
camps and Kakuma camp in Turkana district, down from a maximum of
420,000 refugees in 1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
