<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Strong Pound Keeps Factory Gate Prices Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 15 (Xinhua) - The strong pound has helped keep
the prices of goods leaving the factory gate at their lowest level
for more than 30 years.
</P>
<P>
Cheaper imports meant the price of core goods produced by
British manufacturers rose by 0.3% in the year to March- the
lowest annual increase since July 1967, according to the latest
official figures.
</P>
<P>
The appreciation of sterling by almost 30% since August 1996
has made raw materials bought overseas cheaper while competition
from imported goods has forced UK manufacturers to keep their
prices down.
</P>
<P>
However, the strong pound is not hurting the UK economy despite
the pain for manufacturers as well as exporters.
</P>
<P>
Three-quarters of companies expected higher sales over the next
quarter, and more than two-thirds expected higher profits, showed,
a survey by Dun &AMP; Bradstreet, the credit checking agency.
</P>
<P>
"Despite problems for exporters, we are seeing the economy
performing reasonably well," said Philip Mellor, senior analyst at
Dun &AMP; Bradstreet.
</P>
<P>
On the contrary, the City economists warned that a fall in
sterling could quickly force raw material and producer prices back
up again.
</P>
<P>
Richard Iley, a UK economist at ABN Amro bank, said the
deflationary impact of lower prices would keep inflation subdued
in the short term.
</P>
<P>
"Further out however, underlying inflation should begin to edge
higher," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
