<HEADLINE> U.S. Official Lauds U.S.-Jordanian Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, April 15 (Xinhua) -- A United States government
official said here Wednesday that the "strong ties" between the
U.S. and Jordan are "a base for solving regional problems."
</P>
<P>
Stewart Eizenstat, U.S. State Department undersecretary for
economic affairs, said that U.S.-Jordanian partnership has been
achieved through continuous U.S. economic and military assistance
to Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Such assistance is expected to reach 246 million U.S. dollars
annually in the coming years, said Eizenstat at a seminar
organized by the U.S. Center in Amman.
</P>
<P>
"We are trying to encourage U.S. investment in Jordan, support
Jordan through all possible means and promote regional
cooperation between Jordan and its neighbors," he added.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that with reliable support from the U.S. and
other partners, Jordan has been playing a "constructive and
positive role" in the Middle East peace process and regional
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government very much appreciates such efforts exerted
by Jordan, he added. The kingdom signed peace with Israel in 1994
and has played an active role in promoting peace-making between
Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. is the second largest economic and military aid
contributor to the kingdom after Japan. From 1990 to 1997, it
provided a total of 1.552 billion dollars worth of aid, according
to a press release from the U.S. Embassy in Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Jordan is short on natural resources and strong pillar
industries. Foreign aid has been a major support of its national
economy through the years. 
</P>
