<HEADLINE> Iraq Against Britain's Call for Meeting on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Iraq slammed Britain on Wednesday
for its proposal to hold a meeting in London regarding the
implementation of a oil-for-food program between Iraq and the
United Nations.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the Iraqi Foreign Ministry described
Britain's call as pursuing an anti-Iraq policy with a misleading
and venomous nature.
</P>
<P>
Britain has reportedly called for a meeting to be attended by
various bodies of the oil-for-food program and aid organizations
to work out ways of speeding up the delivery of humanitarian goods
under the program.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has allowed Iraq to increase the oil sale from 2 billion
U.S. dollars to 5.2 billion dollars in every six months to buy food
and medicine under the oil-for-food program.
</P>
<P>
The statement accused Britain of interfering in Iraq's internal
affairs.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has maintained that the affairs relating to the
oil-for-food program should be discussed and decided by Iraq and
the U.N. rather than other parties.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that in 1997, Britain attempted to hinder
the implementation of the oil-for-food program by delaying or
blocking the execution of contracts to deliver humanitarian goods
to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
It accused Britain's representative in the U.N. Sanctions
Committee of having tried to suspend 21 medical contracts that the
World Health Organization has deemed essential to meet the needs
of the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
Britain is continuing its anti-Iraq policy aimed at prolonging
sanctions on Iraq, the statement said, adding that the British
proposal is nothing but a new means to inflict more harm on the
people of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council imposed sweeping economic sanctions
on Iraq in 1990 after its invasion of Kuwait. 
</P>
