<HEADLINE> Cyprus Calls for Peace Moves Within U.N. Framework </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus government proclaimed its
position that any initiatives or moves aimed at reaching a
peaceful settlement in the island must be part of U.N. efforts
toward this end.
</P>
<P>
This stand was made clear here Wednesday after a five-hour
meeting of the National Council, which comprises of the Greek
Cypriot political party leaders.
</P>
<P>
The council, a consultative body to President Glafcos
Clerides, discussed recent developments including Turkish
Cypriots' refusal to continue peace talks and fresh demands for a
change of the basis of negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Government spokesman Christos Stylianides told reporters that
Clerides and Foreign Minister Ioannis Kasoulides briefed the
council on the current situation and talks between Greek and
Cypriot government officials on the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
"The party leaders expressed their views on developments and
the council will meet again at the beginning of May to discuss
matters of strategy," he added.
</P>
<P>
Political party leaders also called for more active engagement
of the U.N. Security Council, including the participation of
Russia and the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus peace process was bogged down after Turkish Cypriot
leader Rauf Denktash's refusal to attend the bicommunal talks in
protest of the EU decision to open talks with the Cypriot
government on its entry into EU.
</P>
<P>
Denktash has said he will not participate in peace
negotiations unless his breakaway state in northern Cyprus is
recognized.
</P>
<P>
The U.N.-led international community has stepped up efforts to
break the current deadlock in the Cyprus peace process and bring
Denktash back to the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
This Eastern Mediterranean island has remained divided since
1974 when Turkey landed its troops and took over the northern
third in the wake of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots declared unilaterally in 1983 a breakaway
"Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus", which was only recognized
by Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
