<HEADLINE> 414 Arrested for Drug Abuse in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The Drug Enforcement Commission
(DEC) has in the first three months of this year arrested 414
people with drugs with a street value of 689.5 million Zambian
Kwacha, or about 400,000 U.S. Dollars, the DEC said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
This was revealed by DEC spokesperson Mukutulu Sinyani at a
one-day anti-drug workshop in Livingstone, a southern border
city, according to Zambia News Agency ZANA.
</P>
<P>
Of those people arrested, said the spokesperson, 392 are
Zambians, while foreign nationals include seven Tanzanians, six
South Africans, three Zimbabweans, two Malawians and one each
from Somalia, India, Lebanon and the Democratic Republic of
Congo.
</P>
<P>
She further revealed that cannabis amounting to 203 tons was
seized in the first quarter and that 90 drug dependent persons
were registered with the DEC.
</P>
<P>
Some of the drugs being consumed and peddled in Zambia include
cannabis and valium, which is a drug for medical prescription.
Others are mandrax, cocaine, etc., said ZANA. 
</P>
</TEXT>
