<HEADLINE> Annan Decides to Pull out UN Investigation Team in Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 15 (Xinhua) -- UN Secretary-General Kofi
Annan on Wednesday decided to pull out the UN team sent to the
Democratic Republic of Congo.
</P>
<P>
The team was sent to the country last August to investigate
reports that forces royal to President Laurent Kabila massacred
thousands of Rwandan Hutu refugees last year.
</P>
<P>
The move came after months of disputes between President
Laurent Kabila's Government and the UN mission over the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the authorities of Kabila detained a Canadian, a
member of the investigation team, and seized some official UN
documents, which leads directly to the withdrawal of the UN team.
</P>
<P>
Pro-Tutsi forces loyal to Kabila are suspected of killing
thousands of Hutu refugees, including women and children, during a
bush war across the former Zaire that resulted the ousting of
Mobutu Sese Seko.  
</P>
