<HEADLINE> Lebanese PM to Visit Egypt on Israeli Offer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik
Hariri is expected to visit Egypt next Tuesday as part of his
diplomatic endeavor to counter Israel's proposal on conditional
withdrawal from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese National News Agency said Wednesday that Hariri will
hold talks with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak on the stalled
Middle East peace process, especially the Israeli offer.
</P>
<P>
For the first time in two decades, Israeli cabinet decided on
April 1 to honor the United Nations Security Council Resolution
425, which calls for an immediate and unconditional Israeli
withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
But it conditioned implementation of the resolution on
negotiated security arrangements with Lebanese government.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon and its ally Syria, which has great influence on
Lebanon, firmly rejected the offer, arguing the resolution asks
Israel to leave Lebanon without any conditions.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the two countries are concerned that the recent
Israeli diplomatic campaign to sell its proposal will isolate
them politically in the world, as the United States has expressed
welcome to the offer and pressed Lebanon to give it serious
consideration.
</P>
<P>
Hariri's visit comes on the heels of a trip by Syrian President
Hafez Al-Assad, who is Cairo to explain to Egypt the Syrian and
Lebanese position over the Israeli move, in an effort to win the
backing from this major power broker in the region.
</P>
<P>
Israel has been occupying a 1,200-square-kilometer area in
south Lebanon since 1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its
northern villages and towns from Lebanese guerrilla cross-border
attack.
</P>
<P>
Syria, which lost its Golan Heights to Israel in the 1967
Middle East war, wants its territory back and has reached a
coordinated stance with Lebanon in dealing with Israel in the
peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
