<HEADLINE> Most EU Members Meet Deadline on Jobs Action Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 15 (Xinhua) -- European Union (EU) member
states Germany, Belgium and Luxembourg failed to meet a Wednesday
deadline for handing in national action plans to tackle
unemployment.
</P>
<P>
The 15 EU member states agreed at the special EU jobs summit in
Luxembourg last November to present their plans to the EU's
executive body, the European Commission, by April 15.
</P>
<P>
It was learned that six EU countries -- Britain, Denmark, the
Netherlands, Ireland, Portugal and Greece -- have already
submitted their action plans.
</P>
<P>
Finland, Austria and Spain had confirmed that they would hand
over their plans later on Wednesday, while France, Italy and
Sweden were also expected to do so.
</P>
<P>
A Commission spokeswoman said that Luxembourg would present its
plan on April 18, Germany on April 22 and Belgium on April 24.
</P>
<P>
She said the Commission had however received all the draft
plans allowing the EU executive to start work on a policy paper
due for the first half of May.
</P>
<P>
"The situation is therefore globally very satisfactory," she
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The action plans will be discussed at the summit of EU heads of
state and government in Cardiff on June 15-16.
</P>
<P>
The plans were designed to incorporate loosely worded
guidelines negotiated at the Luxembourg summit where EU leaders
agreed specific targets to deal with the bloc's jobs crisis.
</P>
<P>
EU unemployment stood at 10.3 percent in February, the lowest
level in five years, but still more than twice the level in the
United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
