<HEADLINE> Delayed Justice Concerning Rwanda Genocide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 15 (Xinhua) -- In the wake of the fourth
commemoration of the 1994 genocide in Rwanda, organizations of
genocide survivors have expressed serious concern about the
failure to render justice.
</P>
<P>
It is in this context that a conference organized by "Ibuka"
(literally meaning Remember) Association deplored the slow pace
at which trials of genocide suspects have been conducted, the
Rwanda News Agency said in a dispatch to Xinhua here.
</P>
<P>
The conference was chaired by the President of the Supreme
Court, Simeon Rwagasore, Laurent Nkongoli, member of parliament,
and the President of AVP -- Association of Peace Volunteers --
Bernadette Kanzayire.
</P>
<P>
"There are so many problems regarding justice in Rwanda," said
Rwagasore. When the new government was set up, the priority was
to put in place institutions, and "Those of justice came later,"
he explained.
</P>
<P>
Rwagasore highlighted the many problems facing the judicial
system in Rwanda, notably the lack of enough personnel, the high
number of people to be judged, and the lack of equipment.
</P>
<P>
"There is much to be done," he underscored, pointing to the
fact that some laws need to be changed.
</P>
<P>
"The problem is not the lack of personnel, justice has been
neglected," charged Nkongoli, calling for the renovation of the
judicial system.
</P>
<P>
For Benadette Kanzayire, justice is an ideal. "Those who
committed genocide should be punished, since they did not only
kill people, they also destroyed the country's economy," she
noted.
</P>
<P>
All the issues raised about the delays in administering justice
will be submitted to the government and parliament, the
conference-organizers resolved.
</P>
<P>
More than 120,000 genocide suspects are currently detained in
Rwandan prisons. Last year only 300 suspects were tried in
Rwandan courts.
</P>
<P>
But so far, none of those found guilty of genocide crimes has
been punished.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that over half a million Tutsis and moderate
Hutus were killed in the genocide in 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
