<DOCNO> XIE19980416.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Calls for Updated Health Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) needs to
update its approach to public health protection in order to meet
the threat of new or resurgent diseases, the European Commission,
the EU's executive body, said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Some of the EU's health policies were formulated up to a
decade ago. Some of the most important health problems didn't
exist then or weren't so visible," a senior Commission official
was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The health of European citizens has never been better,
according to a discussion paper published by the Commission on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
However, it also says that there is still room for major
improvement, adding that one in five Europeans, or 600,000 a year,
will die prematurely before the age of 65.
</P>
<P>
"The population of the 15-nation EU is now aging rapidly and
once-dwindling contagious diseases like tuberculosis are now
making a worrying comeback," the commission official said.
</P>
<P>
The EU's current health protection program, introduced in 1993,
is split into eight categories covering AIDS, cancer, drug
dependence, pollution-related disease, injury prevention, rare
diseases, health promotion and health monitoring.
</P>
<P>
The official explained that some of the emerging health
problems did not fit into these categories, leaving the EU without
the tools to tackle them effectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
