<HEADLINE> Symposium Held in Ethiopia to Deliberate on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Participants of the second
symposium on the federal constitution of Ethiopia Wednesday
pledged to work toward democratic unity and speedy economic
development, before ending the five-day deliberations here.
</P>
<P>
In their five-point resolution, the participants also vowed to
share with the local communities the outcomes of the symposium,
the Ethiopian News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Over 250 participants attended the symposium, including
representatives of federal and regional legislative, executive
and judicial bodies, who were determined to seek ways to amend
civil and criminal codes conflicting with the constitution which
was approved on December 8, 1994.
</P>
<P>
They also pledged to assist women's efforts to ensure their
equality and constitutional rights.
</P>
<P>
Dawit Yohannes, speaker of the House of People's
Representatives, said in his closing speech that a state
structure centered around democratic and human rights has been
put in place.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the symposium would significantly contribute to
the effective implementation of the rights enshrined in the
constitution.
</P>
<P>
The five-day symposium has deliberated on democratic rights,
freedom of opinion and right of women and nationalities.
</P>
<P>
The first symposium on the federal constitution was held four
months ago in Ethiopia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
