<HEADLINE> Tanzanian MPs to Assess Mine Disaster </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 15 (Xinhua) -- A team of three Tanzanian
parliament members left here Wednesday for Arusha in northern
Tanzania to assess the situation of a tanzanite mine where more
than 90 miners are feared to be buried alive.
</P>
<P>
The team, led by Edgar Maokola-Majogo, vice-chairman of the
Parliamentary Standing Committee on Defense and Security, is
expected to present a report to parliament on the casualties and
future remedial measures.
</P>
<P>
The operation to retrieve bodies of the miners are in full
swing. Another seven bodies are reported to be spotted on
Tuesday, but the work to retrieve them seemed to be difficult
because of lack of proper equipment, including submersible pumps.
Earlier, four bodies have been recovered by the rescue team.
</P>
<P>
Daniel Ole Njoolay, the Arusha Regional Commissioner, said the
government could seek assistance from anywhere, including Europe
and South Africa, according to The Guardian newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Fourteen pits at the tanzanite mine collapsed following a
landslide caused by downpour last Thursday evening. Authorities
have offered a list of 55 miners who are presumed dead, but the
death toll could be higher since more miners might have entered
the area to work illegally.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-one miners escaped the disaster thanks to the help of
their colleagues.
</P>
<P>
Tanzanite is a semi-precious stone unique to Tanzania and is
often mined using primitive methods, often without safety
equipment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
