<HEADLINE> S. Leonean Students in Guinea Eager to Go Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of Sierra Leonean
students in Guinea as refugees Wednesday staged a demonstration
in the Sierra Leonean embassy compound in the Guinean capital
Conakry, demanding to be repatriated back home.
</P>
<P>
The students, including those from primary and second schools
and universities, carried with them placards some of which read:
"We are the Leaders of Tomorrow," "We Need Education" and "Send
Us back to Our Classes," the British Broadcasting Corporation
reported.
</P>
<P>
More than 900 students have registered with the Sierra Leonean
embassy for repatriation. Many of them, like other Sierra Leonean
refugees, have given up their rented apartments.
</P>
<P>
However, since the United Nations High Commission for Refugees
(UNHCR) has suspended its repatriation exercise, most of them now
have to find a place for living in the garage in the embassy
compound, the report said.
</P>
<P>
With the new semester approaching, the students have become
increasingly anxious to return home.
</P>
<P>
UNHCR a week ago suspended the repatriation of Sierra Leonean
refugees three weeks after the exercise started.
</P>
<P>
No official reason for the suspension has been disclosed but
reports said it might be partly attributed to Sierra Leoneans who
sold the tickets issued to registered would-be refugees to
businessmen to help them avoid customs duties for their
belongings to be brought into Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that UNHCR is planning a new scheme for the
repatriation but many refugees complained that they could not
afford the transport fare.
</P>
<P>
Following the demonstration, the report said, the embassy has
given assurance to do its utmost to alleviate the price for
Sierra Leonean refugees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980416.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Information Tech Industry Grows Much Faster </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. information
technology, including business on the Internet, is growing twice
as fast as the overall economy, the Commerce Department reported
here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In the latest report "The Emerging Digital Economy," the
department also found that the industry employs 7.4 million
workers, some of whom earn among the nation's highest average
salaries.
</P>
<P>
Traffic on the Internet has doubled every 100 days and Internet
commerce among business will likely surpass 300 billion U.S.
dollars by 2002, the report noted.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the report also found:
</P>
<P>
--The Internet is growing faster than all other technologies
that have preceded it. Radio existed for 38 years before it had 50
million listeners, and television took 13 years to reach that
level. The Internet crossed the line in just four years.
</P>
<P>
--In 1994, about 3 million people were connected to the
Internet. By the end of last year, there were over 100 million
people using it.
</P>
<P>
--Without information technology, inflation in 1997 would have
been 3.1 percent, more than a full percentage point higher than
the 2 percent it was.
</P>
<P>
--Workers in the information technology industry earn an
average of almost 46,000 dollars annually as against an average of
28,000 dollars for the private sector overall. Workers in the
software and service industries are the highest wage earners, at
almost 56,000 dollars annually.
</P>
<P>
The report recommends that governments stay out of the growing
industry, saying electronic commerce shouldn't be "burdened with
extensive regulation, taxation or censorship."
</P>
<P>
Government instead should help provide legal frameworks for
business on the Internet, and rules should result from "private
collective action, not government regulation" whenever possible,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
The department said consumers must be getting more comfortable
making online credit-card purchases: 10 million people in the
United States and Canada had purchased something on the World Wide
Web by the end of 1997, an increase from 4.7 million people six
months earlier.
</P>
<P>
The report also notes a shortage of highly skilled workers and
recommends that students be better prepared.
</P>
<P>
"Countries that have an insufficient supply of skilled workers
will see high-skilled, high-paying jobs migrate to countries that
can supply the needed talent," the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980416.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
