<HEADLINE> NATO Summit Set for April 1999 in Washington </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) will hold a summit in Washington on April 24
and 25, 1999, to mark the alliance's 50th anniversary and to
accept Poland, Hungary and Czech Republic as new members.
</P>
<P>
"We hope to use the upcoming summit meeting in Washington to
welcome the entry of Poland, Hungary, and the Czech Republic as
new members of the alliance," the White House said in a statement
announcing the gathering.
</P>
<P>
The 16-member NATO decided last July to accept the three former
Soviet allies and accession protocols have been signed in December
last year.
</P>
<P>
All the parliaments of the NATO members will have to ratify the
protocols. A vote of two-thirds majority is needed for the U.S.
Senate to approve the plan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
