<DOCNO> XIE19980416.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Planes Send Goods to UNITA From S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Russian aircraft are
allegedly transporting food and military equipment from South
Africa to UNITA rebels in Angola, South African Press Association
(SAPA) quoted police as saying Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
SAPA quoted a police detective service statement as saying
that an official complaint to this end had been received from the
Angolan government last month.
</P>
<P>
Although there was no evidence of arms being flown to Angola,
information was being followed up that military equipment such as
fuel tanks and Tow trucks, clothing, food and mining equipment
were being exported.
</P>
<P>
Police were investigating 200 charges related to
transgressions of the Civil Aviation Act, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
South African Foreign Ministry spokesman Marco Boni said the
alleged exports were in contravention of a United Nations
Security Council embargo on the supply of goods to the National
Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA), except for
humanitarian reasons.
</P>
<P>
"This is illegal as they have no permission from the U.N.
Security Council," he said.
</P>
<P>
The detective service statement said a team comprising members
of the border police unit, the trans-national crime projects unit
and the Civil Aviation Authority visited a Pietersburg aviation
company last week.
</P>
<P>
The Pietersburg airport in Northern Province was said to be
the place where the cargos were transported.
</P>
<P>
Detective service spokesman Faizel Kader said no arrests had
yet been made. He noted that the aircraft belonged to Russian
nationals who lived in South Africa legally.
</P>
<P>
On completion of the investigation, the case dockets would be
presented to the office of the senior public prosecutor for a
decision on possible prosecution.
</P>
<P>
Boni said South Africa was committed to implementing the
mandatory U.N. sanctions against UNITA, and would do everything
in its power to prevent illegal flights to Angola.
</P>
<P>
UNITA, the former rebel movement, and the Angolan government
signed a 1994 Lusaka peace protocol to end the 19-year civil
war, and the U.N. sanctions aimed to force UNITA to implement
the accord and form a national unity government in Angola.
</P>
<P>
According to Boni, South Africa and its Southern African
Development Community partners last year set up regional and
national information centers to control illegal flights to and
from Angola.
</P>
<P>
Last year, South Africa increased its surveillance of airports
from which flights to Angola may depart, he added.
</P>
<P>
A South African private plane was forced down in Angola in
January for flying goods to the region controlled by UNITA.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980416.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-15 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Minister Protests against Police's Raid on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Iran's Minister of Culture and
Islamic Guidance Ataollah Mohajerani on Wednesday lodged a
strong protest against the police for its raid on the offices of
two Iranian daily newspapers Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
According to the Iranian official news agency IRNA, some
policemen raided the lithography sections of the two pro-moderate
newspapers Iran Daily and Hamshahri to control the material which
was going into print.
</P>
<P>
The raid came hours after anti-riot police clashed with
students in a demonstration in front of Tehran University in
support of the detained Tehran Mayor Gholamhussein Karbaschi in
the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
IRNA quoted a press release from the Ministry of Culture and
Islamic Guidance as saying that the minister believed such acts by
the police contrary to the existing laws of the nation, asking
both the judiciary and the police to present an official
explanation for such a move.
</P>
<P>
The police who had assailed newspaper offices showed a check
warrant issued by one of the district courts of Tehran, the press
release said.
</P>
<P>
The ministry sees the necessity of all agencies, organs,
organizations, and departments to abide by the laws governing the
nation, it said, adding that according to Article 24 of the
Constitution, press is free to express their views unless they
run contrary to the interests of the Islamic ideals and common
laws of the nation.
</P>
<P>
According to the press law passed by the Iranian parliament in
1984, no government officials nor non-governmental agencies have
the right to pressure the press, or press for censorship of the
articles or have the right of instant control of the material to
be printed.
</P>
<P>
Iran Daily, which is published by IRNA, and Hamshahri, which is
owned by Tehran Mayor Karbaschi, are the two major newspapers that
supported the mayor after he was detained by the conservative-led
judiciary on charges of embezzlement.
</P>
<P>
Karbaschi was released Wednesday after top Iranian leaders
including the supreme leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei and former
President Hashemi Rafsanjani stepped in to prevent a growing
factional fighting among the moderates and the conservatives over
the issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
