<HEADLINE> King Hussein Stresses Jordan's Support for PNA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Jordan's King Hussein on Wednesday
stressed his country's support for the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) in achieving Palestinian rights.
</P>
<P>
"In compliance with our fixed and clear stand, we consider the
PNA and its president Yasser Arafat as the legitimate authority in
the Palestinian arena," the king said in a message to his prime
minister, Abdul-Salam Majali.
</P>
<P>
"They enjoy our support," he said, "The most valuable thing
between us, that should be maintained and strengthened, is mutual
confidence."
</P>
<P>
He said Jordan's relations with the PNA are based on supporting
it to achieve Palestinians' legitimate rights on their national
soil as well as on their "close coordination and continuous
consultation."
</P>
<P>
The king said that he recently conveyed the "ideas" of the
U.S. government, a major broker in the Middle East peace process,
to the Palestinian and Egyptian leadership respectively in order
to help reactivate the long-stalled Palestinian-Israeli peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
This is the latest sign of Jordan's support for the PNA, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"I found a wise and mature response from the Palestinian
president and senior officials, though the American proposals have
not met the full aspirations (of the PNA)," he said.
</P>
<P>
Jordan as well as other Arab countries appreciate the
Palestinian response, he added.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. proposal demands Israel to pull back from more than 13
percent of the West Bank in exchange for stepped-up Palestinian
efforts to combat terror.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian king lashed out at some Jordanian publications
which attacked the PNA leadership. "These attacks serve only the
enemies of Palestine and Jordan and the march of both peoples," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Jordan, which signed a peace treaty with Israel in 1994, has
been an active mediator between the PNA and Israel. In January
last year, King Hussein helped reach the Hebron accord, under
which Israel commits itself to phased withdrawal from the West
Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
