<HEADLINE> Mubarak, Assad Demand Unconditional Israeli Pullout </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
and his visiting Syrian counterpart Hafez al-Assad Wednesday
demanded an unconditional Israeli withdrawal from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
At a joint press conference here at the end of their two-hour
meeting, the two leaders underlined the importance of Arab
coordination in facing challenges to the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
According to the two presidents, consultations are under way
among Arab leaders on reaching the optimum means for convening an
Arab mini-summit.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak highlighted the importance of the American role in
pushing forward the peace process and voiced conviction that the
U.S. was about to announce its initiative on advancing the peace
process in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace talks have deadlocked for over a
year, while negotiations on the Lebanese and Syrian tracks have
been on ice since March 1996.
</P>
<P>
According to Mubarak, the issue of Israeli security is too
"elastic" to be used as a pretext not to implement what has been
agreed.
</P>
<P>
Syrian President Assad, who arrived here at noon on a lightning
visit, said he was against linking Israel's pullout from south
Lebanon with Syria's withdrawal from Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Al-Assad was accompanied by a high-level delegation, including
Syrian Vice President Abdul-Halim Khaddam and Foreign Minister
Farouq al-Sharaa.
</P>
<P>
"Our meetings in Syria and Egypt are held on a routine basis,
with neither side hiding anything from the other one," said Assad.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak and Assad also tackled the latest developments in the
Middle East, particularly the outcome of the Lebanese-Syrian
summit held in the Syrian resort of Latakia on Monday on the
recent Israeli offer to implement U.N. Security Council Resolution
425.
</P>
<P>
The resolution adopted in 1978 calls on Israel to withdraw from
Lebanon without any conditions. But Israel has said that it would
pull back its troops from Lebanon in exchange for security
arrangements by the Lebanese government.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon has rejected the Israeli plan. Assad and Lebanese
President Elias Hrawi insisted that the withdrawal should be
unconditional, saying the Israeli plan was an attempt to drive a
wedge between them and torpedo the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon and Syria, which is stationing 30,000 troops in Lebanon
as peacekeepers, have agreed not to make peace separately with the
Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Syria wants the Israeli pullback from Lebanon attached to the
return of its Golan Heights, a strategic plateau captured by
Israel in 1967.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian president's visit came a week before a planned
two-day visit to Egypt by Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik Hariri for
talks with the Egyptian leadership on the recent development on
the Lebanese track. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980416.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
