<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The following are the business
briefs from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- An estimated 2 million tourists are expected to
visit Cyprus, the Cypriot Financial Mirror newspaper reported on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
This will be an increase of 5 to 10 percent of tourist number
visiting Cyprus compared with that in 1997, Cypriot Minister of
Commerce, Industry and Tourism Nicos Rolandis said.
</P>
<P>
To promote tourism development, Cyprus so far has invested 1.5
billion pounds (3 billion U.S. dollars) in its most dynamic
economic sector, Rolandis said.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- A United States watchdog has accused Lebanon of
violating regulations of the World Trade Organization as it
manufactures and imports illegal copies of pharmaceutical
products, the Daily Star reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Pharmaceutical Research and Manufacturers of America
announced on Tuesday that it has asked the U.S. government to add
Lebanon to the "watch list" for not protecting intellectual
property.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanon and Oman have signed an agreement on
promoting bilateral trade and investment, the Daily Star reported
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Lebanon's Arab Firm for Consultations and
Marketing will operate as an agent in Beirut for the Omani Center
for Promoting Investments.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The Royal Jordanian and the Omani Airlines Tuesday
signed four agreements, under which Jordan's national carrier will
provide aid to the Omani Airlines in the fields of personnel
training, aircraft maintenance, passenger services, and marketing
and sale methods.


15/04/98 20:26 GMT

NNNN
04:33 04:33 g # PAB
