<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait Projects 5.72-Billion-Dollar Deficit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait has projected its
budget deficit in the coming fiscal year (July 1, 1998 to June 30,
1999) at 1.733 billion Kuwait Dinars (5.72 billion U.S. dollars),
about 10 percent less than previously conceived.
</P>
<P>
The new figure was announced Wednesday by Kuwaiti Deputy Prime
Minister and Minister of State for Cabinet Affairs Nasser
Al-Roudhan at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
He said the cabinet has approved a bill on interlinking budgets
with revenues estimated at 3.127 billion dinars (10.32 billion
dollars) and expenditures at 4.860 billion dinars (16.03 billion
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Of the total sum, 2.577 billion dinars (8.504 billion dollars)
will come from oil revenues and 550 million dinars (1.815 billion
dollars) from non-oil revenues, almost the same as last year.
</P>
<P>
Local reports last month warned that the budget deficit for
the 1998-99 fiscal year is expected to exceed the 2 billion dinars
(6.6 billion dollars) mark for the first time since the sheikdom
was liberated in the 1991 Gulf War from seven-month Iraqi
occupation.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait's projected oil revenues, which account for about 80
percent of the state income, were badly affected by the slump of
oil prices on the world market since the start of this year.
</P>
<P>
As part of an overall move to make up for the shortfall, the
government in February instructed all the ministries and
government departments to cut their budgets by 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
It is also seriously considering reviving plans to impose
charges on various public services in a bid to boost non-oil
revenues.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government also proposed a draft law to stop
transferring 10 percent of state revenues to the country's Future
Generation Fund during fiscal years which record budget deficits.
</P>
<P>
Since 1976, Kuwaiti government has been feeding the fund,
which was drastically depleted by over 20 billion dinars (66
billion dollars) to meet its post-war financial obligations.
</P>
<P>
The draft law stipulate that there should be no cuts from
revenues in years when expenditure exceeds revenues.
</P>
<P>
In January, Kuwait said it had injected 439.1 million dinars
(1.449 billion dollars) of the 1996-97 budget surplus of 502.3
million dinars (1.658 billion dollars) into the fund which now is
unofficially estimated at more than 40 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
