<HEADLINE> Botswana Airwaves Open to Private Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Botswana is opening its
airwaves to private commercial broadcasters, the country's
telecommunications authority said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It invited tenders to set up commercial radio stations
throughout the country. Radio broadcasting had been restricted to
the government-controlled Radio Botswana since independence in
1966, the authority said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The authority invited applications for two licenses, one in
Gaborone, the capital of Botswana, the other in Francistown or
Lobatse, two towns in the country. Bids for licenses in other
towns and villages would be accepted if frequencies are
available.
</P>
<P>
The body said tenders could bid for licenses in more than one
town or village. The body expected programing that would reflect
a broadcaster's social obligations and assist in nation-building.
The national broadcaster was precluded from bidding. 
</P>
</TEXT>
