<DOCNO> XIE19980416.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Finance Minister Says India to Double </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 15 (Xinhua) -- India's Finance Minister
Yashwant Sinha said here on Wednesday that He would strive to
double 1997 foreign investment of 3 billion U.S. dollars during
his first year in office.
</P>
<P>
"Whatever needs to be done will be done to achieve the goal,"
Sinha told U.S. business executives at a breakfast meeting.
</P>
<P>
Sinha was appointed finance minister in India's new coalition
government formed three weeks ago. He is in Washington to attend
the Spring meetings of the International Monetary Fund and World
Bank.
</P>
<P>
Sinha said the Indian coalition government led by Hindu
Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP) wanted to "grow India without
anti-foreignism", which U.S. investors are concerned about. The
Indian coalition would take market-friendly measure to attract
more foreign capital, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Indian government will also seek to boost its export
capability and product quality with a focus on infrastructure,
energy and technology, Sinha said.
</P>
<P>
But "non-priority" areas of imports, which would cover many
consumer goods, would be discouraged, he added.
</P>
<P>
Sinha said he expected India's economic growth at 7 to 8
percent this year.
</P>
<P>
But the IMF in its semiannual World Economic Outlook this
week cut India's 1998 growth estimate to 5.2 percent from 5.5
percent in 1997, citing concerns about political uncertainty and
high interest rates.  
</P>
</TEXT>
