<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bonn Strikes Positive Balance of Telecom Liberalization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 16 (Xinhua) -- German Economics Minister Guenter
Rexrodt said on Thursday that 100 days of liberalization of the
German telecommunications market has achieved positive results
with competition heating up and prices going down.
</P>
<P>
In an assessment of the market opening since January this year,
Rexrodt said that due to private competition, prices for the
long-distance telephone calls had been cut by up to 70 percent in
Germany when compared with the end of last year. Meanwhile
short-distance telephone charges also dropped by up to 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
More than two percent of all telephone calls were now handled
by private operators, a share which was expected to be broadened
to five percent in a few months, he said.
</P>
<P>
Rexrodt also noted that the market opening had also injected
new impetus for growth and job creation.
</P>
<P>
After about 50,000 new jobs had created in each of the past two
year in telecom and information industries, another 100,000 jobs
were expected to be created this year, Rexrodt said.
</P>
<P>
The economics minister also stressed the government's
determination to fully open up the country's post services to
private competition by the year 2003. Currently about half of the
German post market are still controlled by the state monopoly, the
Deutsche Post AG. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
