<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ANZ Bank's Asian Exposure Down 38 Percent in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Australia and New Zealand
Banking Group Ltd. (ANZ), which had its ratings downgraded
recently because of its exposure to Asia, revealed on Thursday its
total exposure to the region had fallen 38 percent to 7.1 billion
U.S. dollars in the six months to March 31, 1998.
</P>
<P>
Chief financial officer Peter Marriott said the bank would
incur some losses from its exposures, but it did not expect its
specific provisions to exceed its standard provisioning policy.
</P>
<P>
He also said the bank's economic and financial forecast for the
region was more positive, and it had confidence in the reform
progress of the troubled nations.
</P>
<P>
"We have confidence in the way that all these countries are
sticking to their reform programs," he was quoted by the
Australian Associated Press as saying.
</P>
<P>
David Ward, a general manager of the ANZ, said the decline in
ANZ's regional exposure would slow over the next six months
because the bank would continue to write business in the region
for its customers.
</P>
<P>
The multi-billion dollar reduction in the bank's regional
exposure occurred because Asian companies met their loan repayment
requirements, and not through writedowns.
</P>
<P>
He declined, however, to reveal the extent of the ANZ's
non-performing loans until the half-yearly profit results are
released next month.
</P>
<P>
"At this point in time we are not disclosing non-accrual loans
or specific provisions because that's part of our May profit
announcement," Marriott said.
</P>
<P>
Two international ratings agencies, Moody's Investor Services
and Standard &AMP; Poor's, downgraded the ratings outlook for the bank
from stable to negative in January and February respectively.
</P>
<P>
In response, Chief Executive John McFarlane said the change in
the ratings outlook was "unduly cautious," arguing that the bank
had been "managing down our overall exposure to Asian-owned
entities whilst preserving relationships with our major clients."
 
</P>
</TEXT>
