<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Patent Cooperation Promotes Technology Exchanges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The Patent Cooperation Treaty
(PCT) requires China to grant 36,534 patents to domestic and
overseas applicants in 1997, a 2.3-fold rise from the figure for
1994, when the nation joined the treaty, according to a
high-ranking patent official.
</P>
<P>
The treaty requires China to research and use the most advanced
technologies invented by enterprises from developed countries,
according to Gao Lulin, commissioner of the State Intellectual
Property Office (SIPO).
</P>
<P>
The World Intellectual Property Organization (WIPO) formed the
PCT which now has 95 member nations. The treaty allows applicants
to acquire worldwide protection if granted an international patent
in their own countries.
</P>
<P>
A number of multinational corporations, including Samsung and
Motorola, have increased the number of patent applications submitted
annually in China.
</P>
<P>
The top ten foreign businesses sumbitted 3,851 patent
applications in 1997, as against 575 in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Strict patent protection and international cooperation
continue to play an active role in China's efforts to attract
foreign investment, according to Gao
</P>
<P>
An increasing number of Chinese enterprises have also made
patent applications in other countries which have signed the PCT.
</P>
<P>
The WIPO is currently organizing a three-day international
symposium in Beijing to discuss the PCT system in the 21st
century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980416.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Toyota Stopping Production As Labor Dispute Delay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 16 (Xinhua) -- A total of 2,500 Australian auto
workers will be affected when Toyota's production line in
Melbourne stops next Tuesday because the ongoing waterfront
dispute is holding up vital car parts on Melbourne's wharves.
</P>
<P>
Toyota Australia President Sam Komori said 45 containers of
components needed for the company's Melbourne production line were
stranded on East Swanson Dock, where union picket lines are
blocking the docks.
</P>
<P>
"So far, all efforts to have the containers taken off the dock
have failed and we are fast running out of parts," Komori said in
a statement released in Melbourne.
</P>
<P>
The auto company will become the first Australian manufacturing
firm forced to halt production by protesting sacked workers
following the sacking of 1,400 unionized dock workers at major
ports across the nation by stevedoring company Patrick last week.
</P>
<P>
The sacking was backed by the Australian government in a bid to
break the 60-year-old monopoly of power of the Maritime Union of
Australia (MUA) and improve dock efficiency.
</P>
<P>
Australian Workplace Relations Minister Peter Reith announced
its political and financial support for Patrick just hours after
Patrick forced its unionized workers out of their posts with
security persons and dogs on April 7.
</P>
<P>
Reith said Toyota's move to halt production next week because
of the waterfront dispute was a damning indictment of the union
movement, and the minister accused the car workers' union, the
Australian Manufacturing Workers Union (AMWU), of putting the
interests of the MUA ahead of its own members by backing the
picket on the docks.
</P>
<P>
Sacked workers and their family members have been protesting
over the their dismissal in major Australian ports, including
Sydney and Melbourne, with hundreds of them blocking the docks.
</P>
<P>
Australian Prime Minister John Howard told Australian
Broadcasting Corporation radio early on Thursday that the
government will not yield to the pressure of the union.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980416.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Exhibition Features Colorful Household Electric Appliances </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The large international household
electric appliances show which opened on Tuesday in Beijing
features colorful appliances which are expected to seriously
challenge the traditional black and white units.
</P>
<P>
The ongoing Household Electric Appliances '98 has served as a
venue for the introduction of new products, with the Haier Group
presenting its Huawangzi (Picture Prince) model refrigerator. the
Italian Ariston-Merloni Household Electric Corp. introducing a
colorful refrigerator series. and the Xiaoya Group premiering its
new washing machine series -- "Rainbow Washers."
</P>
<P>
Chinese consumers began purchasing electric appliances on a
large-scale in the 1980's, with black and white products having
since dominated the market.
</P>
<P>
White has long been the predominant color used for
refrigerators, washers and air conditioners, with black dominating
TV sets and VCRs.
</P>
<P>
European and North American electric appliance manufacturers
have extensively developed colored units in recent years, while
improving quality and introducing new functions.
</P>
<P>
Colorful and decorative household electric appliances have
emerged as the new trend on the international market.
</P>
<P>
A Haier representative said that Huawangzi refrigerators, which
were introduced in Beijing and Shanghai, have received a positive
consumer response.
</P>
<P>
Ariston-Merloni, the first manufacturer in the world to win a
patent for colored appliance technology, plans to introduce its
colored refrigerators to the Chinese market, according to Li
Dubai, manager of the Italian company's Beijing Office.
</P>
<P>
With more money in their pockets, the chinese consumers have
greater discrimination when selecting products, said Li, adding
that his company has full confidence in the Chinese market.
</P>
<P>
"Some consumers, especially young people, are placing increased
importance on the decorative aspects of household electric
appliances, and are at the same time paying more attention to
performance."
</P>
<P>
Industry analysts say that many Chinese families place electric
appliances such as refrigerators and washers in their living rooms
due to limited kitchen space. Decorative electric appliances face
a promising future on the market.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
