<HEADLINE> Malaysia, Uganda to Strengthen Economic Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia and Uganda signed
two agreements on trade and on economic, scientific and cultural
cooperation here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The accords were signed after talks between Malaysian Prime
Minister Mahathir Mohamad and Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni,
said Foreign Minister Abdullah Badawi at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, Museveni proposed that Malaysia consider
investing in Uganda's manufacturing as well as the cocoa, tea and
coffee plantation sectors.
</P>
<P>
Museveni said he also looked forward to having Malaysia
investment in his country's booming hotel and travel industry,
Badawi said.
</P>
<P>
Uganda also sought Malaysia's cooperation in human resources
development, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The prime minister gave the undertaking to assign a minister
as well as a Malaysian trade and investment mission to explore
investment and trade opportunities in Uganda," said Badawi.
</P>
<P>
He said Mahathir expressed Malaysia's keenness in investing in
telecommunications and power generation.
</P>
<P>
"But at the same time the prime minister said given the current
economic problems, the capacity of the Malaysian businessmen and
investors may be a little limited," said Badawi.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia also expressed willingness to hold courses on
privatization and help set up free trade zones and industrial
parks should Uganda require them.
</P>
<P>
Museveni arrived here Wednesday for a four-day visit. 
</P>
