<HEADLINE> Justice Department, Starr Negotiate on Agents' Testimony </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Deputy Attorney General Eric
Holder says the Justice Department is still negotiating with
Independent counsel Kenneth Starr in an attempt to prevent Secret
Service testimony.
</P>
<P>
Starr wants uniformed service personnel to tell what they know
about the relationship between President Bill Clinton and former
White House intern Monica Lewinsky. The independent counsel is
pursuing allegations that the president urged Lewinsky to lie
under oath about an affair.
</P>
<P>
But the Justice Department contends the Secret Service should
have some form of privilege that prevents its officers from
testifying against the president.
</P>
<P>
Starr has reportedly filed a motion with a federal judge in
Washington asking that Secret Service personnel be compelled to
testify before his grand jury.
</P>
<P>
Holder told reporters Thursday, "It's our hope to resolve this
matter short of litigation."
</P>
<P>
While conceding that there is no case law outlining privilege
for Secret Service personnel, Holder said Secret Service privilege
could be established "if there was a general consensus that such a
privilege exists." 
</P>
