Alexander Aguirre said Thursday that the government has
aggressively pursued the drive against graft and corruption which
has reduced bureaucracy and the cases of graft.
</P>
<P>
Aguirre made the statement in response to criticisms from some
presidential candidates against the government's record on
fighting graft and corruption.
</P>
<P>
The Presidential Commission against Graft and Corruption
(PCAGC) in fact reported a declining incidence of graft and
corruption being brought to their attention, Aguirre said.
</P>
<P>
The number of cases filed with the PCAGC peaked in 1994 with
205 cases, but dipped to 115 in 1995, 98 in 1996 and only 45 in
1997, he said.
</P>
<P>
Aguirre said the present government will continue to push its
campaign against graft and corruption in the remaining part of its
term in office.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines will hold its presidential elections on May 11.
President Fidel Ramos will step down when his
constitutionally-mandated single six-year term expires on June 30.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
