<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Higher Commodity Prices Push Australian Stocks Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Higher commodity prices on
Thursday boosted resource stocks and led the Australian
sharemarket to another record closing high.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index improved 10.9 points to 2,881.4 as the
buying in resources offset profit-taking in banks after their
recent surge.
</P>
<P>
The market hit an early intraday record high of 2,893.7 before
easing on some booking of profits and weak Asian markets.
</P>
<P>
"These better metal prices have certainly helped resource
stocks which have been lagging the market recently while the banks
had their run," Steve Mayne from Nevitts said.
</P>
<P>
"The banks fell on a bit of profit-taking and the Asian markets
were a bit weak so we came back this afternoon," he said.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index rose 28.3 points to 1,222.0 after a
strong overnight rise in the copper price to a 1998 high, and
increases also in aluminum, nickel and oil prices.
</P>
<P>
Copper giant BHP Co. Ltd. benefited from the better prices to
improve 46.9 cents to 15.659 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Global miner Rio Tinto also had a marked improvement, closing
50.8 cents higher at 20.75 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index added 5.3 points to 1,303.5 although the bullion
price fell to 306.25 U.S. dollars an ounce, down 2.80 U.S. dollars
from the close in Melbourne on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index fell 6.2 points to 4,958.3 as
investors cashed in on the recent bank rally.
</P>
<P>
ANZ bank shares dropped 13.8 cents to 11.742 Australian dollars
despite announcing on Thursday that its exposure to Asia had
fallen 38 percent since September.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank was unmoved at 23.10 Australian
dollars, Westpac bank had a big 33.7-cent drop to 11.043
Australian dollars while Commonwealth bank was four cents lighter
at 19.45 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover for Thursday was 399.96 million shares at a
value of 807.95 million U.S. dollars, with rises outnumbering
falls 689 to 543. 
</P>
</TEXT>
