<HEADLINE> Iranian Leader Tries to Stop Political Row </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Iran's supreme leader Ayatollah
Ali Khamenei finally intervened Thursday in a political row
between the moderates and the conservatives with a call for unity
and solidarity among the different branches of the regime.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the heads of the government, the judiciary and the
legislature, Khamenei said the main feature of the Islamic
political and social system is unity and solidarity, the Iranian
official news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
If all forces in the country join hands to keep hoisted the
flag of Islam with amity and sympathy, the hope sparked in the
hearts of the Muslims will be kept alive, he said.
</P>
<P>
Khamenei's call came one day after the release of the moderate
Tehran Mayor Gholamhussein Karbaschi, who was detained on April 4
by the conservative judiciary on charges of embezzlement.
</P>
<P>
The mayor's detention triggered a power struggle between the
moderates and the conservatives and brought the government of
President Mohammad Khatami and the judiciary headed by Ayatollah
Mohammad Yazdi to stand against each other.
</P>
<P>
Khamenei warned against magnifying some of the problems and
blowing small flaws out of proportion.
</P>
<P>
"We are still at the beginning of the road" to build the
country and bring the Islamic civilization before the world, he
said.
</P>
<P>
He cautioned that traces of attempts to create tension and rift
among the people can be found in the propaganda of the enemies
outside the borders and in the attempts of their followers inside
the country as well as by those whose interests have been damaged
by the revolution.
</P>
<P>
He called on the people to support the government, the
judiciary and the legislature, saying that all are duty-bound to
support both the administration and the judiciary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
