<HEADLINE> China Utilizes 10 percent More Directly-Invested Overseas Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 16 (Xinhua) -- China brought in 8.59 billion
U.S. dollars in directly-invested funds from overseas businesses
in the first quarter of this year, up 9.68 percent over the same
period last year, according to the Chinese Ministry of Foreign
Trade and Economic Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The government approved 3,971 projects invested by overseas
businesses during that period, with the contractual value
amounting to 8.72 billion U.S. dollars, a ten percent increase.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, funds introduced by Sino-foreign joint ventures from
overseas businesses dropped 4.06 percent to 3.4 billion
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Sino-foreign cooperative businesses and solely foreign-funded
firms brought in 1.98 and 3.12 billion U.S. dollars in overseas
funds, respectively, up 35 and 12.53 percent.
</P>
<P>
All the three types of businesses posted increases in the
amount of their newly approved contracts involving overseas funds,
reaching 3.16, 1.88 and 3.61 billion U.S. dollars, respectively,
up 10.85, 0.75 and 13.69 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
