<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Pushes Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar pushed
higher on Thursday but was largely sidelined as the market focused
on the U.S. dollar and the Japanese yen.
</P>
<P>
The local currency lifted as high as 65.15 U.S. cents before
closing at 65.00 from 64.72 on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"With interest rates on the back burner, the Australian dollar
has been offered some well-earned relief," Colonial State Bank
Chief Economist Craig James said.
</P>
<P>
A number of factors have weighed on the Australian dollar in
recent weeks, including speculation about a cut in official
interest rates, weakness of the Japanese economy, the Australian
waterfront conflict, and sluggish commodity prices.
</P>
<P>
However, Wednesday's G7 meeting has put the focus back on the
yen.
</P>
<P>
In a communique issued after the meeting of world finance
ministers in Washington, members of the Group of Seven top
industrial nations welcomed steps taken by Japan to stimulate its
economy, but appeared to offer little support for Tokyo's drive to
bolster the sagging yen.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin confirmed the country's
strong U.S. dollar policy remains in place and added that the G7
meeting did not discuss the possibility of joint intervention in
the currency markets.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar was at 85.43 yen from a close of 83.57 on
Wednesday, and at 1.1754 Deutsche marks from 1.1658 marks.
</P>
</TEXT>
