<HEADLINE> China To Train IPR Experts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 16 (Xinhua) -- China is determined to train
experts on intellectual property rights in order to stimulate the
nation's economic growth and serve related global protection,
according to a senior Chinese official.
</P>
<P>
Addressing an ongoing international symposium on intellectual
property protection, Zhou Guangzhao, vice-chairman of the Standing
Committee of the National People's Congress (NPC), disclosed that
the Chinese government recently established the China Intellectual
Property Rights Training Center, the first of its kind in the
country.
</P>
<P>
"The center will be the pivotal education base for nurturing
intellectual property professionals," he said.
</P>
<P>
Eleven well-known intellectual property experts have been
invited to teach at the center, according to officials from the
State Intellectual Property Office (SIPO).
</P>
<P>
The center will also collect the latest academic works for
training programs and will regularly organize international forums.
</P>
<P>
"Establishment of the center will alleviate the severe shortage
of the IPR specialists in China," said Zhou.
</P>
<P>
"We will strengthen the cooperation with the World Intellectual
Property Rights Organization and strive to be the WIPO's key base
in the Asia-Pacific Region," said Gao Lulin, Commissioner of the
SIPO, the organization which will administer the new training
center.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the Chinese government upgraded the office in
charge of intellectual property rights to a department directly
under the State Council. China also adopted its first patent law
in 1993.
</P>
<P>
WIPO Deputy Director-General Francois Curchod expressed full
support for the Chinese training center. 
</P>
</TEXT>
