<HEADLINE> Good Progress in Clean-up of Dead Fish: HK Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Good progress is being made in
the clean-up of dead fish as a result of a toxic red tide, a Hong
Kong official said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Secretary for Economic Services Stephen Ip completed a
helicopter inspection of the clearance exercise over Tolo Harbor,
Sai Kung, Kat O and Lamma Island Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
He said the northeastern part of the water surface of Hong Kong
was basically cleared of dead fish. Only off Lamma Island there
was still a small quantity of dead fish to be collected.
</P>
<P>
About 120 tons of dead fish was scavenged Thursday. The Marine
Department is working from dawn to dusk, deploying a total of 51
vessels in the operation. The exercise is expected to continue
over the next few days until all the dead fish is disposed of.
</P>
<P>
The red tide raged through most of Hong Kong fish culture zones
during the last few days, incurring heavy losses to local fish
farmers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
