<HEADLINE> Record Seizure of Pirated Compact Discs in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 16 (Xinhua) -- About 840,000 pirated compact
discs (CDs) were seized in a joint operation by Hong Kong's
anti-graft and customs officers, the Customs and Excise Department
(CED) said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Independent Commission Against Corruption (ICAC) and Customs
officers Wednesday raided a pirated CD storage center located in
an industrial premises at Tsuen Wan, the "New Territories."
</P>
<P>
"This is a record seizure effected in a single storage location
and the value is estimated at about 26 million HK dollars (3.3
million U.S. dollars)," said a CED spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Officers found that over 54,000 copies of the pirated CDs are
of an obscene nature.
</P>
<P>
Initial inquiries indicated that about 15 percent of the goods
in question were from Taiwan. Follow-up investigations are
continuing, the spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
The crackdown followed an unprecedented joint swoop on April 8
when 24 people were arrested and 320,000 pirated music and video
CDs and production equipment were seized.
</P>
<P>
The Customs, in conjunction with other Law enforcement
agencies, has once again demonstrated the full commitment to
eradicating piracy in Hong Kong, protecting the rights of
copyright owners and preserving the good image of Hong Kong, the
spokesman noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
