<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   South Korea to Build City with International Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 16 (Xinhua) -- South Korea will start this year to
build a city by attracting international investment with extremely
good conditions, South Korean Construction and Transportation
Minister Lee Jung-moo said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The city will occupy an area of 66 million square meters on the
Yongjong and Yongyu islands, some 65 kilometers to the west of
Seoul. It will be linked to the Inchon International Airport,
which, now under construction, will reportedly replace the Seoul
Kimpo International Airport.
</P>
<P>
Lee Jung-moo said the construction of the city will cost four
billion U.S. dollars and create 300,000 jobs. The government will
exempt various taxes on its infrastructure construction.
</P>
<P>
The city, to be finished in the year 2020, could become a
center for international business in the Asia-Pacific rim and a
logistics hub for the region.
</P>
<P>
Relevant regulations related to international investment are
being formulated, added the minister. 
</P>
