<HEADLINE> Nigerian Foreign Minister Accuses EU of Funding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Foreign Minister Tom
Ikimi Wednesday accused the European Union (EU) of encouraging
subversive elements in the west African country by funding their
activities.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the 54th session of the United Nations Commission
of Human Rights (UNCHR) in Geneva, Ikimi said the EU has set
aside three million European Community Unit (about three million
U.S. Dollars) in its 1998 budget to support the so-called
pro-democracy activities in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
"We are aware that in spite of our protest, these funds have
been made available and are now being secretly disbursed in
Nigeria to finance subversion through out the country," said
Ikimi.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister reiterated his government's commitment to
protecting human rights of all Nigerians, and vowed to resist
attempts by some powerful nations to dictate to the country what
system of government it must operate and who its leader should
be, said a report reaching here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He accused these nations of using human rights as tool to
project their narrow foreign policy interests and objectives.
</P>
<P>
Ikimi stressed the need to make efforts at all levels to
recognize the importance of consultations and dialog among member
states, not only for the promotion of human rights, but also for
enhancing international relations as a whole.
</P>
<P>
He urged the UNCHR to adopt a pragmatic and forward-looking
approach to the issue of human rights, by not adopting any
resolution against Nigeria and removing the item of human rights
situation in Nigeria from its agenda.  
</P>
</TEXT>
