<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-16 11:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Wants Israeli Pullback Offer Linked to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 16 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
has said Israel's offer to pull back from south Lebanon would be
more effective if it is linked with a similar move on the Syrian
track.
</P>
<P>
"The British government regards this (Israeli) stance as a
positive step, and that the application will be easier if progress
would be made within the context of a comprehensive settlement
mainly on the Syrian track," he told the Arabic daily Al Ahram in
an interview published Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Israel decided on April 1 to endorse the U.N. Security Council
Resolution 425, but conditioned a pullback from south Lebanon on
making security arrangements with the Lebanese government.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon and Syria, wanting a full and unconditional Israeli
withdrawal from south Lebanon as well as the Syrian Golan Heights,
have rejected the Israeli plan as an attempt to drive a wedge
between them. Peace talks between Israel and the Lebanese and
Syrian sides have been stalled since February 1996.
</P>
<P>
The interview was published a day before Blair starts a two-day
visit to Egypt Friday on the first leg of his Mideast tour aimed
at pushing forward the peace-making. He will also visit Saudi
Arabia, Jordan, Israel and Palestinian self-rule areas.
</P>
<P>
Blair said he looks forward to meeting Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak to discuss a host of issues of mutual interest,
especially the stalemated Mideast peace process and the current
Arab conditions.
</P>
<P>
Britain, the current holder of the rotating EU presidency, and
other EU member states feel deeply concerned over the
"disappearance of Madrid's and Oslo's spirit," Blair said,
referring respectively to the 1991 peace conference in the Spanish
capital and the Palestinian-Israeli peace agreement signed in Oslo.
</P>
<P>
He said the EU members give top priority to the peace issue
thanks to their economic and historical ties as well as their
vital interests with countries of the region.
</P>
<P>
"We should earnestly work to set up confidence among parties
and to float ideas that could contribute to boosting the
U.S. drive to bring about peace in the region," said the prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
Dismissing worries that the U.S. might "wash hands off" the
stalled peace process, he assured that "Washington will not pull
out from the peace process in the Middle East", adding that the
European role will be complementary to the American one.
</P>
<P>
As for the current situation in Iraq, Blair mentioned about
Bratain's attitude toward the U.N. sanctions on Iraq and the
keenness that humanitarian assistance reaches the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
"If Iraq honors its pledges, cooperates with U.N. arms
inspectors and applies what was cited in U.N. Secretary General
Kofi Annan's memorandum, then talks will start about lifting those
sanctions," he said.
</P>
<P>
Iraq negotiated a deal with the U.N. in February, which helped
avert imminent U.S. and British military strikes and paved way for
unfettered U.N. arms inspections in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions imposed on Iraq after its 1990 invasion of Kuwait
can not be lifted until the U.N. gives it a clean bill of health
on destroying its weapons of mass destruction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980416.0124 </DOCNO>
