<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Product Quality Improves at Large, Mid-Size Companies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Large- and mid-size companies
continue to perform well in quality control checks compared with
small enterprises, according to an official inspection report for
the first quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Large enterprises were given a quality rating of 93.3 percent,
up 4.6 percent from the previous quarter, while mid-size companies
had an average rating of 91.9 percent, their highest record since
1995, according to the report, which was released by the State
Bureau of Quality and Technical Supervision (SBQTS).
</P>
<P>
Both quality ratings are above average for the 1,050 companies
checked, or 76.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The product quality of the country's large- and mid-size
manufacturers has been improving steadily during the past few
years, said an official with SBQTS, adding that this may help some
state-owned enterprises solve the problem of slow sales.
</P>
<P>
He said that the comparatively low quality rating of small
enterprises, which stood at 70.2 percent in the first quarter of
this year, is the major factor hindering the progress of the
average quality rating.
</P>
<P>
The report also indicated that quality problems with some
medical equipment, food and mining equipment were still serious.
</P>
<P>
SBQTS has already urged technical supervision departments at
all levels to resolve these problems, listed in the report, and
pay special attention to products closely related to people's
health and safety.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
