<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Baby Giant Panda Passes Health Examination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 16 (Xinhua) -- A baby giant panda, weighing 160
grams when its was born, has passed an examination by experts in
the Beijing Zoo and been awarded a health certificate.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Jinguo, the zoo's deputy director, said the giant panda,
named "Ben Ben," was born in July and was not up to health
standards at one month old.
</P>
<P>
Ben Ben's mother, Yong Yong, was 16 years old and very sick
when giving birth to Ben Ben and another 80-gram panda, who was too
weak to survive.
</P>
<P>
Before Ben Ben, Yong Yong had delivered seven pandas.
</P>
<P>
Ben Ben's weight reached 8,700 grams 100 days after its birth
and was in good health because of the panda keepers' efforts.
</P>
<P>
Ben Ben now weighs 33 kilograms and its health is normal.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing Zoo has 14 giant pandas, 13 of them artificially bred.
</P>
<P>
Giant pandas are considered an endangered species. There are
about 1,000 giant pandas worldwide, most of them living in
southwest China's Sichuan Province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980416.0129 </DOCNO>
