<HEADLINE> DPRK Delegation Hosts Dinner for ROK Counterparts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Negotiators from the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea hosted an evening working dinner for
their Republic of Korea counterparts, according to sources from
ROK.
</P>
<P>
Negotiators for the two sides held last-minute talks in a bid
to narrow remaining gaps. However, no information has been
released concerning the location and results of the dinner meeting.
</P>
<P>
The first high-level direct contact between the two sides in
four years adjourned this morning following a two-hour closed-door
session which showed no signs of tangible results following
a break on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We engaged in serious talks during today's meeting, and
time for the next round of talks will be determined and scheduled
during further contacts," according to Chun Kum Chul, leader of
the DPRK delegation.
</P>
<P>
ROK delegation leader Jeong Se Hyun pointed to the lack of
progress during the morning session.
</P>
<P>
However, one DPRK delegate was quoted as saying that the
delegation does not want to go home empty-handed.
</P>
<P>
Local observers note that it is too early to predict the
outcome of the dinner meeting which might, in fact, lead to
further talks.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, both sides agreed to remain in Beijing for an
additional two days following the unsuccessful third round of full
meetings which failed to yield an agreement concerning fertilizer
supplies from the ROK.
</P>
<P>
The two sides remained in contact on Thursday, with each
waiting for the other side to take the first step needed to spark
the resumption of talks. Neither side has shown a willingness
to make concessions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
