<HEADLINE> MTN Promises to Establish 89,000 Lines in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Mobile Telephone Network (MTN)
has promised to establish 89,000 lines in the next five years in
Uganda, The New Vision reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
John Nasasira, Ugandan minister of works, transport and
communication, yesterday told the paper after a signing ceremony
of the licence of the second national operator to the MTN, a
South Africa led consortium.
</P>
<P>
The MTN consortium is to deposit with the government a credit
letter of four million U.S. dollars to secure the commitment, the
minister said.
</P>
<P>
This is in addition to the MTN's bid payment of 5.6 million
U.S. dollars and a licence fee of 200,000 U.S. dollars. The
investment was over 60 million U.S. dollars in the next five
years. MTN has paid up 5.8 million U.S. dollars for the licence,
he added.
</P>
<P>
The licence has clauses protecting consumers against potential
abuses, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Jacques Sellschop, the MTN corporate public relation excutive,
said MTN will start testing its network within three or four
months and commercial services could commence shortly thereafter.
</P>
<P>
"Phones are no longer facilities for a privileged few,"
claimed Charles Mbiire, the MTN Uganda chairman.
</P>
<P>
MTN is a South African telecommunication giant. It holds 50
percent of MTN consortium's share. The other shares are kept by
the Swedish based Telia Overseas with 30 percent and Rwanda
registered Trister Investment S.A.R.L. and Uganda's Invesco (U)
Limited with 10 percent each.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan government granted the licence to MTN to break
monopoly in telecommunication in the country. Uganda has devided
Uganda posts and telecommunications into two separate firms: The
Uganda Posts Limited and The Uganda Telecommunications last year.
Earlier reports said the two firms are to privatise later to
improve services and management. 
</P>
</TEXT>
