<HEADLINE> Heavy Rains Hampers Somali Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Reports from the Southern
Somali regions of Lower and Middle Jubba indicate that heavy
rains are posing difficulties in both the business and
humanitarian activities in those regions.
</P>
<P>
According to local elders in the Southern port town of Kismaio
and the flood stricken town of Bu'ale, the Gu' season rains have
already begun seriously cutting off many roads within and outside
these towns.
</P>
<P>
On the continuing humanitarian efforts, a World Food Program
convoy which left the port town of Merca, 100 km south of
Mogadishu, last week is yet to reach its destination.
</P>
<P>
The head of loading and transporting firm of the food aid,
Ahmed Mohamed Farah (Hilweyne) said that 319 tons of lentils,
ground maize and cooking oil still remain stuck in the district
of Sakow.
</P>
<P>
Hilweyne said the WFP food convoy is destined to the town of
Bu'ale which has seriously been affected by the floods last year.
</P>
<P>
Four trucks out of the 26 food convoy remained stuck in a mud
27 km south of Sakow town until last night before making to the
town of Sakow yesterday, Hilweyne said.
</P>
<P>
Hilweyne declared that the road situation in the region
doesn't permit them to continue their journey while the heavy
rains still continue falling.
</P>
<P>
The food convoy is accompanied by four battle wagons and quite
a number of heavily armed militiamen. Some of the food convoy was
also destined to Salagle village, 105 km West of Bu'ale town
where people are reportedly suffering the most because of the
past disastrous floods.
</P>
<P>
Inside the Southern port town of Kismaio, 500 km South of
Mogadishu, the rains have hindered the local business activities
closing down many shops and business places. The business of the
town has already been shattered by the recent clan-based clashes
between the Majerten and Marehan subclans over the control of the
town.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of this week, the rains have been falling
heavily in the towns of Kismaio, Jamama, Hagar and Bu'ale where
the inter-business between these towns have been cut off after
pools of water have once again been created in the roads already
ruined by last year's floods. 
</P>
</TEXT>
