<HEADLINE> Investigators Probe Fatal Coal-Mine Accident in Henan Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The April 6 coal-mine explosion
in central China's Henan Province was mainly caused by the fight
for resources among individual employers, according to
investigators of the accident.
</P>
<P>
The death toll from the explosion in three shafts in
Pingdingshan City now stands at 55.
</P>
<P>
The three shafts, which were connected, are all unlicensed and
their employers illegally conducted mining beyond the allowed
sites, local officials said.
</P>
<P>
To obtain more resources, dynamite was fired in one shaft to
block it but the explosion spread into the other two.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government is holding urgent meetings to ensure
safe production and investigating the accident.
</P>
<P>
Li Chengyu, deputy governor of Henan, said the province will
stop approving new small mines. Any mine that was unlicensed
or fails to meet safe production standards will be shut down, he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
