<HEADLINE> Beijing Taking Steps to Expand Service Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Beijing Vice-Mayor Zhang Mao said
here today that the city will take measures to vigorously develop
the service sector.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a seminar on the development of the service trade in
Beijing, he said the local government will first open service
markets in the economic and high-tech zones while forming
international service trade companies with the capacity to provide
funds, professionals, management and technology.
</P>
<P>
Beijing will foster more entrepreneurs, business people,
financiers and lawyers familiar with this trade, Zhang said, and
try to guide enterprises in extending their business overseas.
</P>
<P>
Zhang, who is in charge of Beijing's foreign trade and economic
affairs, pledged that the municipal government will work out
measures to support the development of the service trade.
</P>
<P>
For example, the government will give priority to the service
trade in terms of granting loans, tax exemptions, land use and
technological equipment, he said.
</P>
<P>
Zhang also outlined key sectors of the service trade that
Beijing will develop in the near future such as international
travel, finance, insurance and telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
He said Beijing already has a sound foundation for developing
these sectors. The international travel and service sectors have
become a main source of foreign currency earners.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the service sector accounted for 53.8 percent of the
city's gross domestic product, topping other cities in China.
</P>
<P>
Beijing received 2,298,000 foreign tourists in 1997, and earned
foreign currency worth 2.25 billion U.S. dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
