<HEADLINE> Shanghai Gets Internet Stock Trading Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 16 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese stock trader now can do
trading in A-shares on the Shanghai Stock Exchange in just seconds
if he or she has access to the Internet, no matter where he or she
is.
</P>
<P>
Starting on Wednesday, an electronic trading system developed by
the Shanghai branch of the Communications Bank, Minfa Securities
Co., and Shanghai Information Port provided automatic transfer
services from bank accounts to the exchange through the Internet
Shanghai Hotline.
</P>
<P>
Any Internet user who wants to buy or sell A-shares (reserved
for domestic traders only) can do so by getting a Pacific credit
card at Communications Bank and a Minfa Securities account there
or at Minfa offices.
</P>
<P>
Minfa officials say they can guarantee the confidentiality and
security of the trading because of a code-word system.
</P>
<P>
The system also provides instant access to stock quotes and
information every eight seconds.  
</P>
</TEXT>
