<HEADLINE> Nigeria Seizes 1,360 Tons of Indian Hemp in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 16 (Xinhua) -- About 1,360 tons of Indian hemp
were seized across Nigeria in 1997, the country's National Drug
Law Enforcement Agency has said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the Nigerian Television Authority Hausa service
Wednesday, NDLEA chairman, Major-General Musa Bamaiyi said the
cultivation and trafficking in Indian hemp has assumed serious
dimension in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
He blamed the increased rate of drug trafficking in Nigeria on
the political misunderstanding between Nigeria and the U.S.,
which he said has given traffickers the leeway to engage in their
nefarious trade.
</P>
<P>
Bamaiyi urged the U.S. to co-operate with Nigeria in the fight
against drug trafficking and money laundering, saying that it
would be beneficial not only to the two countries, but to
humanity at large.
</P>
<P>
He also warned staff of the NDLEA to desist from corrupt
practices or be booted out of service.
</P>
<P>
"There are bad eggs in NDLEA who will arrest suspects and ask
them to pay certain amounts of money to regain their freedom," he
said, adding that NDLEA would not condone such practices.
</P>
