<HEADLINE> Share Prices Plunge in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices tumbled in Tokyo
Thursday with the key Nikkei index closing below the 16,000 line
for the first time since April 7.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange plummeted 415.53 points, or
2.55 percent from Wednesday's close to 15,883.77.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, sank 24.11 points, or 1.94 percent to
1,217.34.
</P>
<P>
Trading on the First Section went up to an estimated 400
million shares from Wednesday's 280 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Nippon Steel was Thursday's most heavily traded issue.
</P>
<P>
Traders said arbitrage unwinding pulled down stock prices,
after the outcome of Wednesday's meeting of top financial
officials from the Group of Seven (G-7) industrialized nations
failed to impress the market.
</P>
<P>
Market players had expected G-7 officials to pressure Japan to
implement further economy-boosting measures and hence help boost
Tokyo stocks, but the G-7 statement was weaker than expected, they
said.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,328 issues listed on the First Section, losers far
outpaced gainers 939 to 207, with 110 issues remaining unchanged.
</P>
</TEXT>
