<HEADLINE> Myanmar FM Arrives in Dhaka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar Foreign Minister U Ohn Gyaw
arrived here Thursday on a three-day visit to Bangladesh, to
discuss bilateral issues, particularly the repatriation of
Rohingya refugees, border trade and cooperation in joint ventures.
</P>
<P>
The 66-year-old foreign minister, who is leading a five-member
delegation, was greeted at the airport by his Bangladeshi
counterpart, Abdus Samad Azad.
</P>
<P>
U Ohn Gyaw, who is also member of the Myanmar-Bangladesh Joint
Border Commission, is the highest-ranking Myanmar official to
visit Bangladesh since June 1996, when the present Awami
League-led government was formed.
</P>
<P>
Repatriation of some 21,000 Rohingya refugees at different
transit camps in Cox's Bazar, southeast Bangladesh, would be the
major topic of official discussions on Friday, reports said.
</P>
<P>
The two sides are also expected to discuss repatriation of
Myanmar nationals from Bangladeshi jails, removal of land mines
from border areas, the conclusion of a treaty on demarcation of
land boundary, expansion of border trade, and demarcation of
maritime boundary.
</P>
<P>
A total of 250,000 Rohingyas crossed Bangladesh border in 1991,
and about 230,000 of them have been repatriated under joint
supervision of Bangladesh and Myanmar governments and the United
Nations High Commissioner for Refugees.
</P>
<P>
The repatriation process, however, has remained stalled since
July 1997 reportedly as a result of the refugees' refusal to
return. 
</P>
