<HEADLINE> Indonesian President Calls on Students to Return to Class </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Soeharto has
called on the protesting students to return to class and develop
their competitiveness in order to face the future.
</P>
<P>
"The president asked that students continue their studies so
that they could become competitive people," Minister of Education
and Culture Wiranto Arismunandar said Wednesday evening after
meeting with Soeharto, official Antara News Agency reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"This (competitiveness) is important because otherwise we would
not be able to have national resistance, economic, political and
cultural resistance," the minister quoted Soeharto as saying.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of students kept up their demands for reforms and
lower prices of basic commodities Wednesday at campus rallies
organized concurrently at dozens of universities in the country.
</P>
<P>
At least four campuses in Jakarta witnessed noisy rallies
demanding a reshuffle of the cabinet, a clean government, lower
prices of commodities and the empowerment of the House of
Representatives, the "Jakarta Post" daily reported.
</P>
<P>
Students in big cities have staged demonstrations since
February this year, blaming the government for the economic crisis
and demanding political reforms.
</P>
<P>
In some cities, students held hunger strikes and clashed with
police.
</P>
<P>
Wiranto reiterated his earlier warning that rectors should not
allow student politics on campus, but said students or lecturers
were free to engage in political activities outside campuses and
in their private capacity.
</P>
<P>
"I hope the ban on conducting practical politics on campuses is
positively responded to in this development era ...," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Some cabinet ministers have held dialogues with the
representatives of students, but the latter asked for meeting with
President Soeharto directly.
</P>
<P>
House Speaker Harmoko said earlier that President Soeharto
would hold talks with students some time in the future as long as
it is necessary for national development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
