<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Launches National Biodiversity Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia Thursday launched
its National Policy on Biodiversity with the aim at conserving the
country's abundant but threatened plants, wildlife and
micro-organisms.
</P>
<P>
The policy, first mooted four years ago to transform the
country into a world center of excellence in conservation,
research and utilization of tropical biological diversity by the
year 2020, will serve as a toll to guide policy makers on striking
a balance between development and the environment.
</P>
<P>
The policy, among other things, sets out to maintain and
improve environmental stability for proper functioning of
ecological systems, ensure long term national food security and
preservation of the unique national biological heritage for
present and future generations.
</P>
<P>
Its other goals are to optimize economic benefits from
sustainable utilization of the components of biological diversity,
enhance scientific and technological knowledge in the field and
emphasize biosafety considerations in the development and
application of biotechnology.
</P>
<P>
There are 87 programs proposed under the policy to conserve
biodiversity and ensure sustainable use of its components.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia has been identified as one of the 12 "megadiversity"
countries which, with the greatest biological diversity in the
world, hold 60 to 70 percent of the global biodiversity with
Malaysia having 15.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Launching the policy at the National Science Center here,
Science, Environment and Technology Minister Law Hieng Ding said
the policy would be implemented by all sectors to guide policy
makers in ensuring that Malaysia's rapid development was done in a
sustainable manner.
</P>
<P>
Law said "With the implementation of the policy, we will also
look at current environmental laws if there is a need to amend
them." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
