<HEADLINE> Majority in UK, Ireland Back N.Irish Accord: Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 16 (Xinhua) -- About three quarters of voters on
both sides of the Irish border would say "yes" to the historic
Northern Ireland peace accord in next month's referendum, an
opinion poll showed on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The joint Guardian-Irish Times opinion poll showed a
surprisingly strong majority support for the peace agreement
struck last Friday.
</P>
<P>
In Northern Ireland, 73 percent would vote for the accord,
while in the rest of Britain, 81 percent would back the peace
deal. In the Republic of Ireland, 61 percent of voters would show
their favor if they were asked to vote.
</P>
<P>
The accord, which maintains Northern Ireland's links with
Britain but also builds cross-border bridges with the Irish
republic, is being put to referendums north and south of the
border on May 22.
</P>
<P>
According to the poll, support for the agreement is
particularly strong among the supporters of Sinn Fein and the
Ulster Unionist Party, the two major feuding parties in the
province. Four-fifths of Sinn Fein supporters backed the accord
and only seven percent were against.
</P>
<P>
David Trimble, leader of the Ulster Unionist Party, welcomed
the poll and forecast that his party council would overwhelmingly
back him at a crucial weekend meeting.
</P>
<P>
"It is the best deal available -- warts and all," he told BBC
Radio. "We have stuck to the course." 
</P>
</TEXT>
