<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia, Uganda Sign Trade Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia and Uganda signed
here Thursday a trade agreement to provide a conducive framework
for the two countries to enhance trade cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The main objective of the agreement is to expand and deepen
trade, economic and industrial cooperation between Malaysia and
Uganda, an official press release said.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement signed by Malaysian International Trade and
Industry Minister Rafidah Aziz and Ugandan Minister of State for
Planning and Economic Development, the two sides will grant each
other the most-favored nation status in matters relating to custom
duties and foreign trade formalities in import and export.
</P>
<P>
The two sides will facilitate each others' participation in
trade fairs and exhibitions which include exemptions from custom
duties and other charges for samples intended for exhibitions and
fairs.
</P>
<P>
The agreement also provides for the establishment of a joint
trade committee to discuss measures to enhance two-day trade.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, bilateral trade between Malaysia and Uganda totaled
17.5 million ringgit (4.729 million U.S. dollars) and for the
period of January to February this year, trade between the two
countries amounted to 0.39 million ringgit (0.105 million
dollars), according to the latest official figures.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's main export items to Uganda were radio-broadcast
receivers, garments, furniture and parts, footwear and printed
matter while its main import items from Uganda were cotton and
fresh, chilled or frozen fish.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed after talks between visiting Ugandan
President Yoweri Kaguta Museveni and Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohammad who witnessed the signing.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan president arrived here Wednesday for a four-day
state visit to Malaysia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980416.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PC Chip Market Growth to Slowdown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Worldwide sales of the most
widely-used primary chips in personal computers will rise only by
16 percent, according to a U.S. market research firm Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Dataquest Corp. based in San Jose, California, said that
slowdown of x86 microprocessor sales reflects collapsing
prices. Chip sales rose by 24 percent in 1997 from the previous
year.
</P>
<P>
The drop is primarily because of lower average selling prices
of microprocessors, Dataquest said. The price of an average PC has
dropped from 2,000 dollars to about 1,000 dollars, forcing
chipmakers to cut their prices, said the company.
</P>
<P>
In February, Dataquest cut its forecast of worldwide
semiconductor market to 160 billion dollars in 1998, saying that a
continuing overcapacity would force manufacturers to keep price
low.
</P>
<P>
About 90 percent of the world's computers use the chips of
x86. Intel is the inventor of the standard and is the biggest
producer. But now its rivals sell x86 chips for much cheaper.
</P>
<P>
Dataquest said that most of the worldwide microprocessor
revenue growth in 1998 would come from sales of chips for high-end
desktop machines, known as workstations, or for servers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980416.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea to Further Open Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Foreigners, from April 16 on, are
free to buy up to one-third of the stocks in all listed companies
in South Korea except those related to defense industries,
according to the Finance and Economy Ministry Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investors will also be allowed to completely take over
local companies as from next month, the law said.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean government will soon unveil 81 defense-related
industries, which will remain off-limits to foreigner investors,
said the ministry.
</P>
<P>
The ministry added that a bill which will allow foreign
businessmen to buy all stocks of listed companies without the
approval of the Board of Directors is under discussion.
</P>
<P>
The bill, which is expected to be considered at a cabinet
meeting next Tuesday, will be submitted to an extraordinary
session of the National Assembly (the parliament) for approval.
</P>
<P>
The bill is designed to attract as much foreign investment as
possible, said the ministry.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement signed last December with the International
Monetary Fund for a rescue loan of 57 billion U.S. dollars, South
Korea, the financially troubled nation, has to completely open its
market and conduct economic restructuring this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
