<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Plant Species at Risk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 16 (Xinhua) -- South Africa has lost 53
plant species to extinction, an alarming rate to the country
which is renowned for its rich and unique flora, a senior
environment conservationist has warned.
</P>
<P>
Ian MacDonald, chief executive of the World Wildlife Fund
(WWF) South Africa, said "the sense of pride South Africans have
in this fact is dampened by our inability to manage bio-diversity
successfully."
</P>
<P>
"The loss and potential loss of plant diversity as indicated
in the red list should be a primary concerns for all South
Africans," MacDonal said at the launch of the 1997 World
Conservation Union red list of threatened plants.
</P>
<P>
The list, the result of 20 years work by scientists,
conservation organizations, botanical gardens and museums,
reports that at least one in every plant species world wide is at
risk of extinction.
</P>
<P>
The red list reveals that 12.5 percent (about 34,000) of the
world's plant species are threatened.
</P>
<P>
In South Africa, claimed to be the most thoroughly studied
country on the African continent, 11 percent of the nation's
20,000 plant species are at risk.
</P>
<P>
WWF South African officials have expressed commitment to
rectifying this sorry state of affairs and was working with
numerous other organizations in the battle to save flower and
plant species. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
