<HEADLINE> Share Prices Decline Sharply on Singapore Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Share prices declined sharply
on the Singapore market as the benchmark Straits Times Industrials
Index (STII) lost 28.79 points to close at 1,515.15 points on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said the market sentiment was affected by news of
ratings down-grades by Standard &AMP; Poor's on four local banks,
while negative corporate news from Malaysia also pulled buyers out
of the market.
</P>
<P>
Banking shares suffered the brunt of the selling in the wake of
rising interbank rate, they noted.
</P>
<P>
The total market volume fell slightly to 219.94 million units,
valued at 327.44 million Singapore dollars (204.65 million U.S.
dollars). Declines overwhelmed advances by 265 to 74, while 253
other counters remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
MBf Capital was the most actively traded counter as it
registered a turnover of 20.29 million units. It was followed by
Rekapac which had 10.94 million shares traded. Malaya Resources
was next with 10.18 million shares changed hands.
</P>
<P>
Local computer sound card maker Creative 50 led the gainers of
the day as it rose by 70 cents to finish at 36.7 Singapore
dollars. CenProp increased by 50 cents to end at 10.5 Singapore
dollars. NatElec was up by 14 cents to close at 3.18 Singapore
dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, SPH (Singapore Press Holdings) was the biggest
loser as it declined by one dollar to end at 16.4 Singapore
dollars. DBS (Development Bank of Singapore) Foreign Right fell by
83 cents to close at 1.93 Singapore dollars, while DBS Foreign
Right100 was 70 cents lower at 1.99 Singapore dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
