<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Divorce Easier in S. Africa as New Law Enforced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Divorce in South Africa is
easier as the Divorce Court Amendment Act comes into force, the
Justice Department said in a statement Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The act adopted in 1997 has been put into effect from April 6,
1998, the department said.
</P>
<P>
"This act makes divorce courts, which were previously only
accessible to a particular population group, now open to all
population groups throughout the republic."
</P>
<P>
"Any person now has the choice to either approach the high
court or the divorce courts in order to obtain a divorce," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
No legal representation is required at divorce courts and it
is hoped that this would make divorce procedures uncomplicated
and affordable.
</P>
<P>
Through the commencement of the act, the laws relating to
divorce are now uniform throughout the country, the department
said.
</P>
<P>
Previously, divorce laws differed in the former self-governing
states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
