<HEADLINE> China To Improve Medical Aid to Foreign Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 16 (Xinhua) -- China will establish hospitals,
pharmaceutical factories and service centers in a number of
foreign countries and regions as part of its medical aid to them.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of doing so is to promote bilateral cooperation
between China and the recipient countries, Chinese minister of
Health Zhang Wenkang said here today.
</P>
<P>
He noted that China will not only send medical teams to foreign
countries but also jointly run hospitals and pharmaceutical
factories abroad in order to promote the export of medical
facilities, pharmaceuticals, medical materials, and traditional
Chinese medicine and technology.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said medical aid should become an important channel for
Chinese companies entering foreign markets and boosting
multi-level, wide-ranging and mutually beneficial economic and
trade cooperation with foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
Since China sent its first medical team to Algeria in April of
1963, more than 16,000 doctors and other medical workers have been
assigned to over 60 countries and regions in Asia, Africa, Latin
America and Europe, offering treatment to 220 million foreign
patients and training some 2,000 local doctors and medical
personnel, according to Zhang.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese minister made the remarks at a meeting, which was
held in the Great Hall of the People here today to mark the 35th
anniversary of China's first overseas medical team. At the
meeting, some medical units and doctors were honored for their
outstanding contributions in the field. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
