<HEADLINE> Canadian Defense Minister Ends Visit to Kuwait </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Defense Minister
Arthur Eggleton ended his official visit to Kuwait Thursday, during
which he held talks with senior Kuwaiti officials on Kuwaiti
procurement of Canadian arms.
</P>
<P>
"We have talked about the Kuwaiti government procurement and
what the Canadian defense industry has to offer," Eggleton told
reporters Wednesday on board the Canadian frigate HMCS Toronto.
</P>
<P>
The patrol frigate carrying 239 sailors on board, is currently
on mission in the Gulf and docked at Kuwait's Shuwaikh port last
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Eggleton said the response of the Kuwaiti government to the
talks is "very positive," but adding that no agreement has been
materialized so far.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that Canada would be able to sell some of
its military products to Kuwait. Canada has been trying to sell
Kuwait warships and military trucks.
</P>
<P>
Eggleton, who arrived in Kuwait Monday, held talks with Kuwaiti
officials on Canadian commitment to maintaining peace and
stability in the Gulf region.
</P>
<P>
Before leaving for Gaza to continue his Middle East tour,
Eggleton reasserted Canada's support for peace and stability in
the region and for the integrity of Kuwaiti borders.
</P>
<P>
He also held talks with Kuwaiti leaders on holding joint
military maneuvers within the framework of bilateral cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Ninety-eight airmen of the 435 Air Squadron of Winnipeg, have
been in Kuwait since early March. The Canadian forces were part of
Ottawa's contribution to the multinational forces that rushed to
the Gulf earlier this year to ensure Iraq's compliance with an
agreement it signed with U.N. over weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
Eggleton said the deployment of more Canadian troops to the
region depends on Iraq's compliance with U.N. resolutions, adding
that withdrawal of current troops from the region is possible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
