<HEADLINE> China to Tighten Control on Liquor Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 16 (Xinhua) -- China plans to crack down even
further on fake alcoholic products to protect famous brands in the
next few years, a Chinese official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference in Beijing, Zhu Mingxian,
deputy-director of the State Bureau of Quality and Technical
Supervision, called on the technical supervision departments at
all levels to inspect all the liquor manufacturers and tighten its
management over production certificates.
</P>
<P>
Those firms producing substandard liquors should halt
production and make restitution, and those that do not have
production certificates should be dealt with in line with the law,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said liquor market inspections should focus on the
elimination of shoddy and unqualified products, while paying
attention to the protection and publicity of name-brand products.
</P>
<P>
In the next three years, the bureau will choose a group of
liquor products and test samples of famous brands from 30 major
Chinese cities each year to guarantee their quality, he said.
</P>
<P>
During the Spring Festival period, several kinds of liquors
spiked with methanol caused 19 deaths in Shuozhou City of north
China's Shanxi Province. The Shanxi Xinhuacun Group Company,
which produces two famous brands of spirits, had its sales volume
drop sharply because it was located beside one of the fake spirits
manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
The two famous brands, Fen Yew and Zhu Ye Qing, are up to the
state standards in terms of quality.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980416.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
