<HEADLINE> China's Largest Bank Reports Stable Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The Industrial and Commercial
Bank of China (ICBC), the country's largest bank, reported stable
business in the first quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
The value of ICBC's local currency deposits by the end of March
was 43 billion yuan more than that at the beginning of the year,
while its foreign currency deposits increased 420 million U.S.
dollars in value, according to bank statistics.
</P>
<P>
ICBC extended 378.2 billion yuan in loans in the first quarter,
raising its value of outstanding loans to 7.4 billion yuan more
than at the start of the year.
</P>
<P>
A breakdown shows that state-owned businesses accounted for 74
percent of the first quarter's increased working capital loans for
industry, which were valued at 14.3 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
ICBC plans to increase its yearly loan portfolio by 200 billion
yuan this year, of which 75 billion yuan will be extended in the
first half to ensure the realization of China's 8 percent economic
growth rate this year.
</P>
<P>
To that end, the bank has to attract an additional 250 billion
yuan in deposits this year.
</P>
<P>
A bank source said that ICBC this year will issue its loans
mainly for railway, highway, telecommunications, public utilities,
and new- and hi-tech projects.
</P>
<P>
He added that the bank's loans for housing construction and
mortgages will total 25 billion yuan this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
