<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aid Workers Kidnaped in Mogadishu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 16 (Xinhua) -- A Kenya pilot was among nine
International Red Cross workers kidnaped by gunmen in Mogadishu
Wednesday after they landed at an airstrip north of the Somali
capital, local press reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The gunmen arrived aboard four "technicals" -- pick-up trucks
with heavy weapons mounted -- and fired in the air to scare off
the lightly armed airstrip guards, witnesses were quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The airport guards did not attempt to intervene and ran off to
hide in tea kiosks, the witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
The gunmen also kidnaped a Somali working for the local Red
Crescent Society.
</P>
<P>
It was said the kidnappers were members of the Da'ud subclan
of the Abgal, loyal to north Mogadishu strongman Ali Mahdi
Mohamed.
</P>
<P>
The gunmen took the expatriates and the Somali -- who were
unhurt -- to the Karan district in the north of the divided
capital, said the witnesses.
</P>
<P>
They were seen there in a high-walled compound belonging to a
feared militia commander, Ahmed Adley, said the press reports.
</P>
<P>
The kidnapping was confirmed in Nairobi by Josue Anselmo,
spokesman for the International Committee of the Red Cross
(ICRC).
</P>
<P>
He said the aid workers flew to Mogadishu to carry out various
evaluation missions in the anarchic nation which has been hard
hit by months of torrential rains.
</P>
<P>
"We are trying our best to sort out the crisis," he said.
</P>
<P>
Somalia has been ruled by competing warlords since the
overthrow of dictator Mohamed Siad Barre in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Seven of the expatriates work for the ICRC, including two
pilots, and two for the International Federation of Red Cross and
Red Crescent Societies, said Anselmo.
</P>
<P>
Besides the Kenyan, the other victims were an American, a
South African, a German, a Belgian, A French, two Swiss and a
Norwegian.
</P>
<P>
Ali Mahdi is himself in Nairobi, where earlier this week he
reached an agreement with three other Mogadishu leaders to reopen
the main port and international airport by the end of his month.
He said he did not know about the kidnapping.
</P>
<P>
"I don't know what happened. But if it's true, they will be
released immediately," he said.
</P>
<P>
The kidnappers made no immediate demands. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
