<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liberia Accused of Planning to Destabilize S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian military Thursday
accused Liberia of planning to destabilize neighboring Sierra
Leone where order is being restored after the fall of the
coupists and reinstatement of the legitimate government.
</P>
<P>
There are enough proofs to show that the government of
President Charles Taylor wanted the situation in Sierra Leone to
be unstable, Col. Godwin Ugbo, acting Director of Defense
Information, told Xinhua over the phone.
</P>
<P>
This is the first official allegation from the Nigerian
military that brings to open the rift between Taylor and Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
According to the defense spokesman, the Liberian government is
training 3,000 of its soldiers in Libya to fight the West African
Peacekeeping Force (ECOMOG) along the border between Sierra Leone
and Liberia.
</P>
<P>
"This is based on security reports available to ECOMOG high
command," he said, adding that the soldiers being trained are
expected to soon become part of Sierra Leone's rebel
Revolutionary United Front (RUF) and junta forces to fight ECOMOG
at the border areas.
</P>
<P>
"It has been established that Taylor is aiding and abetting
the RUF in Sierra Leone because he does not want stability in
Sierra Leone."
</P>
<P>
"This is wrong but he wants instability in Sierra Leone so
that Liberia, his own country, will be stable," the spokesman
claimed.
</P>
<P>
It has long been reported that Taylor does not like Nigeria
especially after his overwhelming victory towards Liberia's top
seat was checked by the Nigerian-led ECOMOG in early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG arrived in Liberia at the invitation of the then
President Samuel Doe in 1990 when Taylor launched an offensive
against the Doe administration, triggering off the seven-year
bloody civil war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
