<DOCNO> XIE19980416.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Sees Reduction in Election-Related Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Philippine National Police
Director General Santiago Alino Thursday said there would be a 50
percent reduction in election-related violence in the coming May
11 elections compared to previous polls.
</P>
<P>
Alino made the remark on account of comparative studies made by
the police which said there was one election-related violence
every two days in the 1995 congressional elections.
</P>
<P>
In the 1995 polls, there was a total of 121 violence cases, of
which 65 percent took place before the elections and the rest
happened on the election day.
</P>
<P>
Alino attributed the expected decrease in violence cases this
year to the early deployment of police forces in expected poll hot
spots nationwide and the strict implementation of the campaign
against loose firearms and private armed groups.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that insurgency groups pose the biggest threat
to the coming elections. However, the National People's Army (NPA)
had announced ceasefire with government troops while the Moro
Islamic Liberation Front was engaged in talks with government
negotiators.
</P>
<P>
According to Alino, the most recent incident was the burning of
a candidate's vehicle by NPA rebels when the candidate refused to
pay 120,000 pesos (3,157 U.S. dollars) as taxes to the rebel
group.
</P>
<P>
During the 1992 presidential elections, more than 100 people
were killed in the outbreak of violence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
