<HEADLINE> Death Toll of S. African Crash Rises to 31 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The death toll of a horror
crash near Newcastle in South Africa's Kwazulu-Natal province has
risen to 31 Thursday, South African Press Association (SAPA)
reported.
</P>
<P>
The dead included 23 school children. Over 50 other people
were wounded.
</P>
<P>
The disaster occurred shortly after 3 p.m. (1300 GMT) and five
vehicles were involved. Four of the vehicles, including a school
bus and a horse and trailer, fell into a 50-meter embankment.
</P>
<P>
Kwazulu-Natal transport spokesman Ranjeni Munusamy said four
children and one adult had died overnight, bringing the number of
deaths to 31.
</P>
<P>
Eighteen people, including 15 children, were killed at the
scene Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Newcastle police spokesman Godfrey Nyembe, who visited the
scene of the accident, said many of the people had been seriously
injured.
</P>
<P>
"I cannot put into words what a terrible, terrible accident
this was. There were young people crying for help, young children
crying for help, young children with gaping wounds.
</P>
<P>
"It was complete chaos. I have never seen anything as
terrible," Nyembe said.
</P>
<P>
A minibus, which was also involved in the accident, remained
on the road.
</P>
<P>
An investigative team flew to the scene to determine the cause
of the accident. Munusamy said bad weather was thought to be one
of the possible causes.
</P>
<P>
He said Kwazulu-Natal chief official for transport, Sibusiso
Ndebele, would fly to Newcastle Thursday morning to visit the
scene of the accident, and discuss with Newcastle mayor the
possibility of setting up a special fund to assist the victims
and their families.  
</P>
</TEXT>
