<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Owner Spends Big Money in Zambia's Copper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Roan Antelope Mining Corporation
of Zambia has invested an additional 69 million U.S. Dollars to
refurbish the mine plant and buy new equipment for Luanshya
Copper Mine in Zambia's Copperbelt Province.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, it has already spent 105 million dollars in various
new mining projects in the mine.
</P>
<P>
Zambia Daily Mail Thursday quoted the corporation's General
Manager Sam Phiri as saying in Luanshya that the corporation is
working to turn the whole mine around by improving operations and
work on new projects has begun with the extension of the mine
below 2,800 feet level.
</P>
<P>
The newly privatized mine has formulated the new projects to
resuscitate the mine through the construction of an open pit
mine, where experts are already conducting feasibility studies,
according to the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Phiri said the corporation has already committed 20 million
dollars for the refurbishment of the plant and machinery and
another 26 million dollars will be spent within the next 18
months for capital replenishment.
</P>
<P>
He said three million dollars has been committed for the
feasibility studies.
</P>
<P>
With the new projects and huge investment in place, the
current output of 45,000 tons of finished copper will be
increased to 65,000 in the next two and half years and to 100,000
tons by the year 2003.
</P>
<P>
The corporation is also contributing to the community
rehabilitation in Luanshya with a pledge of five million dollars
a year for the health, schools, sewer services and garbage
collection.
</P>
<P>
Due to copper price falls in the international market and
outdated equipment, lack of investment and mismanagement, annual
copper output of the country, one of the biggest copper-producing
countries in the world, has decreased gradually to about 300,000
tons in recent years.
</P>
<P>
To attract foreign investments, advanced technology and
management to revive the stagnating copper production, the
government has invited foreign tenders for the mines and assets.
</P>
</TEXT>
