<DOCNO> XIE19980416.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Ethiopian Govt Helps Youth in Employment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The Ethiopian government has
paid much attention to the unemployment and other problems facing
youth and has taken measures to help young people support
themselves.
</P>
<P>
As one of the least developed countries, Ethiopia, with a big
population of over 58 million only after Nigeria and Egypt in
Africa, certainly faces the problems of youth unemployment and
absence of sufficient job opportunities for school dropouts.
</P>
<P>
According to a recent report of the Ethiopian Herald, a large
number of school dropouts and those who have completed high
school education but with no opportunity to go to higher learning
institutes, could not remain dependent on their parents or
guardians with meager income. However, a considerable number of
them spend almost half of their life-time in such a state.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the youths, particularly those from low income
families often become hopeless and juvenile delinquents.
</P>
<P>
Surveys have indicated that during the past decade, 75 percent
of the young population in urban areas have remained unemployed.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian government and pertinent departments have paid
more attention to the young people's unemployment problem, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
They not only train jobless youngsters in technologies for job
opportunities, but also provide government institutes and private
enterprises with staffs and workers with professional skills.
</P>
<P>
Firstly, they educate youths by positive measures including
providing them with study materials, recreational facilities and
other leisure time activities.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, they encourage parents to regularly advise
their children and teach them good manners.
</P>
<P>
Similarly, strong relationship is encouraged between and among
parents, schools, society and the youths themselves in order that
the latter can be well-nurtured so as to develop an all-round
personality.
</P>
<P>
In order to address the multifaced problems of the youth, the
government departments have already forwarded proposals to
initiate the adoption of national youth policy, according to the
report.
</P>
<P>
Once such policy comes into effect, it will be possible to
devise different strategies and action-oriented programs directed
towards alleviating youth-related problems and empower them to be
actively engaged in the national development activities.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, the Ethiopian government has implemented a
vocational training policy to open up job opportunities to many
youths.
</P>
<P>
A nationwide effort is going on for forming youth associations
and students councils so that the youth and students can be
organized.
</P>
<P>
The vocational training courses run by various government and
non-governmental organizations in Ethiopia have proved
successful.
</P>
<P>
About 12,000 youth in northern Tigray region have become
self-supportive after receiving various vocational trainings run
by the Tigray youth association in the past few years.
</P>
<P>
Thirteen jobless high school girl graduates have completed a
three-month fast training course and received certificates in
Addis Ababa recently, according to a report of the Ethiopian
Herald.
</P>
<P>
In a similar development, jobless youth in Ethiopia's northern
Amhara region have been trained to become self-supportive. Some
1,052 youth have been trained in carpentry, masonry and other
trades in three training centers of the region since 1994, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
Most of the trained young people are now employed by
government and private organizations.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the trained youths have also organized themselves
by setting up their own joint ventures and small enterprises.
</P>
</TEXT>
