<DOCNO> XIE19980416.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Expert Explains Tax System on Internet Commerce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The United States opposed new
taxes on the Internet but would consider levying Internet shoppers
to ensure existing sales tax revenue was not lost in the shift to
cyberspace shopping, an adviser to U.S. President Bill Clinton
said here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the Australia's first summit on electronic commerce
attended by about 350 Australian government ministers, business
and research leaders, Ira Magaziner, senior policy adviser to
President Clinton, said that any new approach would have to be tax
neutral, signaling it was looking to shift the onus for tax
collection on to the shopper.
</P>
<P>
"We are opposed to any new or discriminatory taxation on
Internet or on electronic commerce," Magaziner told the two-day
meeting, which began on Thursday, organized by Australian National
Office for the Information Economy and Australia's
telecommunications giant Telstra company.
</P>
<P>
"What we want is a uniform, simple automatic approach based
upon principles of tax neutrality, and no discriminatory taxation.
So we are not proposing any new tax of any sort," he said.
</P>
<P>
Industrialized nations were discussing ways to take existing
value-added tax and sales tax and apply it to Internet
transactions in a neutral way, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We are favoring legislation in the United States which would
create a moratorium on the application of any new taxes on
Internet commerce," Magaziner said.
</P>
<P>
"And then the creation of a commission among the states and
cities and counties in order to develop a uniform approach to the
collection of taxation."
</P>
<P>
Magaziner has completed a document recently outlining the U.S.
government's strategy for promoting the development of global
electronic commerce on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. was keen to develop the approach over the next few
years, with a new way of collecting taxes but not a new tax, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that as the Internet takes off, electronic commerce
takes off, more companies will do more business, they'll make more
money and we automatically get our share," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The best thing for us to do is do nothing, just to let it go,"
he concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980416.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Top Judge Stresses Judicial Fairness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The President of the Supreme
People's Court Xiao Yang has told a national meeting on judicial
work that China needs a contingent of superior judges to ensure
judicial fairness and safeguard the sanctity of the law.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the judiciary need to put themselves under
supervision by the press and that they should discipline
themselves and protect the rights of the people by implementing
the law and being fair in their verdicts.
</P>
<P>
They need to win the trust and support of the people, he said,
and there should be a check on their conduct. To do that, the
court personnel system should be reformed, Xiao says, and a system
of judicial supervision introduced, and the relations between
judges and prosecutors, defendants and lawyers should be clearly
defined.
</P>
<P>
Courts should invite people's congress deputies and members of
Chinese people's political consultative conferences to hear cases
and participate in judicial work.
</P>
<P>
The Supreme People's Court and courts at various levels should
set up offices or even open special telephone lines for people to
report judicial misconduct, Xiao says, and with the exception of
cases involving national security, privacy, or juvenile
delinquency, every case should be handled openly and be covered by
the news media. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
