<HEADLINE> S.Korea's Top 30 Conglomerates to Sell 200 Subsidiaries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 16 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's top 30 conglomerates,
or chaebols, are working to sell some 200 affiliated companies,
said the Federation of of Korean Industries (FKI) Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The conglomerates have been trying to sell those businesses
since the current financial crisis occurred late last year, said
Sohn Byung-doo, Deputy Chairman of the FKI.
</P>
<P>
FKI is the interest group representing leading family-owned
chaebols of the nation, which has been in a serious financial
crisis caused by a slew of corporate bankruptcies and bad loans of
financial institutions since late 1997.
</P>
<P>
In an apparent response to President Kim Dae-jung's open
criticism against the top conglomerates' slowness in reforms, Sohn
said the chaebols have no choice but to restructure to survive the
IMF period.
</P>
<P>
"Trading 200 businesses is a big job and has to be done with
great discretion," said Sohn.
</P>
<P>
President Kim Monday said he was not satisfied with the "pace
and great discretion," Sohn added.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement signed with the government, the top 30
chaebols have to take serious self-reform steps, including the
sell-off of real estate and ailing subsidiary companies, to raise
funds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
