<HEADLINE> Boeing Increasing Cooperation With Chinese Airlines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The US Boeing has said it will
enter the Chinese market further by training Chinese pilots and
maintenance workers and selling more planes to the country, a
Boeing official has said.
</P>
<P>
Boeing will invest more in training Chinese for the 21st
century, and this year, more than 13 million yuan has been set
aside to train more than 40 Chinese managers in Seattle's Boeing
Institute, said Jiande Chen, a Boeing official in charge of China
affairs, in a recent interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Boeing has, so far, invested several hundred million US dollars
in helping develop infrastructure, with emphasis laid on further
improving safety, increasing capacity, and management skills. In
addition, 6,000 Chinese have attended professional courses,
technical seminars, and other activities in the US and China.
</P>
<P>
Boeing has 288 of its airliners operating in China, accounting
for 70 percent of the nation's civil aircraft, with 142
Boeing-737s, the most popular airliner in the world, operating
with 24 of the country's 34 air carriers.
</P>
<P>
With the rapid growth of China's civil aviation, it is expected
to need about 1,900 jetliners over the next 20 years, about 140
billion US dollars worth of planes. With that bright a future,
they expect good gains, Chen said.
</P>
<P>
China and Boeing started cooperating 26 years ago, when China
first ordered ten Boeing-707s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
