<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sugar Output Rises in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's sugar production
recorded a slight improvement last year with 401,000 tons
compared to 389,000 tons in 1996.
</P>
<P>
A report compiled by the U.S. embassy attributes the
improvement to better management of factories, enhanced
processing efficiency and the ability of sugar companies to move
stocks that rose in 1996 to the market, the Daily Nation
newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The report projects production for this year will be 410,000
tons and consumption, 484,000 tons, including 27,000 tons to be
exported to the region.
</P>
<P>
The report says that the newly-installed equipment at Mumias
Sugar Company contributed to increased production but also points
out that the new diffuser technology does not cope well
over-mature cane carried over from other seasons.
</P>
<P>
Constraints hindering expansion of area under the crop include
high production costs, limited suitable land and delayed harvests
which tend to discourage farmers from growing cane.
</P>
<P>
The industry still faces many problems especially low
processing efficiency due to old machinery, poor maintenance and
management, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
"Low processing efficiency, capacity and decaying transport
infrastructure have led to delayed harvesting in almost every
zone of production," it says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
