<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trade Between Kenya, Britain up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's trade with Britain is on
the increase and the east African country is now the second
highest exporter of goods to Britain from sub-Saharan Africa, the
Daily Nation newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Trade volume between the two countries rose by 2.3 percent in
1997 with the value of merchandise exports up from 191.3 million
pounds in 1996 to 195.7 million pounds last year, according to
the latest data from the Overseas Trade Statistics.
</P>
<P>
However, Britain's exports to Kenya fell in the same period
from 241.1 million pounds to 238.2 million pounds.
</P>
<P>
The figures confirm the recent trend of British exports to
Kenya falling while those from Kenya have been rising.
</P>
<P>
Only South Africa now sells more goods to the Britain from
Africa than Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The main exports by Kenya are tea, coffee and horticultural
products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
