<DOCNO> XIE19980416.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Turned into "Mud City" By Spring Rain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Early-rising Beijingers today
found a city coated with a thin layer of mud -- roads, houses,
tree leaves, bikes and cars.
</P>
<P>
The thunderstorm that awakened many residents around midnight,
however, was the usual springtime phenomenon. And the rain lasted
less than an hour.
</P>
<P>
"It counts merely as a light one at most, with a rainfall of
only two or three millimeters," said Ding Deping, an expert with
the Beijing Meteorological Bureau.
</P>
<P>
He said a strong breeze from northern Inner Mongolia and the
Loess Highlands made a surprise attack on Beijing last night,
blowing up dust from the loose soil.
</P>
<P>
The rain was enough to coat the dust and was not strong enough
to wash it away, leaving mud stains on the face of the city, Ding
said.
</P>
<P>
Those most seriously affected by the "muddy rain" were the
city's drivers, whose vehicles all were dotted with yellowish
stains today. Washing cars became a hot business in the city.
</P>
<P>
A car-washing shop near the China Art Gallery put out a
handwritten sign saying "quick mud-washing" early this morning. Its
employees were busy waiving rags at drivers to woo business.
</P>
<P>
Longtime residents say dusty weather used to often plague
Beijing in early Spring, but massive planting of trees and grass
in recent years has reduced the dust problem.
</P>
<P>
Ding said construction sites were another cause of the dust and
sand floating in the air.
</P>
<P>
Forecasters at the Beijing Meteorological Station predict more
dusty weather because of strong winds. When the mud dropped on
the ground dries, it once again is picked up by the wind to float
in the air. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980416.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Ceramics Industry Going Through Good Period </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 16 (Xinhua) -- China's ceramics business, which
has an 8,000-year history, has been seeing some fast growth, with
nearly 10 billion pieces produced annually, or about 60 percent of
the world's total output.
</P>
<P>
China is the world's largest producer of ceramics for everyday
use, with markets in over 150 countries and annual exports worth
1.9 billion US dollars, according to Liu Jingzhou, deputy-head of
the China Council for the Promotion of International Trade's
Building Materials Branch.
</P>
<P>
Liu says that China has a number of key ceramics production
centers in Tangshan and Handan in Hebei province, and Zibo in
Shandong, Yixing in Jiangsu, and Jingdezhen in Jiangxi.
</P>
<P>
The country also has research and design institutes, colleges
and a large group of specialized enterprises for ceramics.
</P>
<P>
China has at least 1,000 producers of ceramics for everyday
use, some of which are introducing technology and equipment from
abroad to improve production. Other improvements include reducing
pollution and cutting energy consumption.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
