<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Compaq Nearly Makes No Profit in First Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Compaq, the world's biggest
personal computer maker, reported Wednesday that flat computer
sales nearly wiped out its entire profit for the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
The company said it earned 16 million U.S. dollars, or just one
cent a share during the quarter, compared with 414 million
dollars, or 27 cents per share, in the same period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
First quarter sales for Compaq totaled 5.7 billion dollars, an
8 percent increase over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The company attributed the narrow profit margin to the "price
war". Compaq said it had cut prices of its business desktops more
steeply than expected due to intense competition for corporate
customers.
</P>
<P>
Another factor, said Compaq's President and Chief Executive
Officer Eckhard Pfeiffer, is that sales from North American
commercial channels were not meeting expectations.
</P>
<P>
Compaq is the fifth largest computer company in the world and
the biggest supplier of personal computers, with worldwide sales
of 24.6 billion dollars in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
