<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Technique Makes Use of Subterranean Warm Water in Tianjin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists have developed
a new technique for using subterranean hot water resources in the
city of Tianjin, the biggest port in northern China.
</P>
<P>
An 8,700-sq-km underground pool with more than 220 billion
cubic meters of hot water was found in Tianjin, the largest region
of mid- to low-temperature geothermal resources in China. The
water lies from 60 to 3,000 meters deep, has a high mineral
content, moderate temperature, and is suitable for daily use.
</P>
<P>
The technique employs double wells, one for pumping up hot
water, the other for replacing it to prevent surface subsidence
and pollution. They were drilled in an urban area, the pumping
well at 1,494 meters and the replenishing well at 1,590 meters. As
many as 112 cubic meters of hot water are pumped from the first
well every hour and 152 cubic meters pumped into the other.
</P>
<P>
The city has drilled 300 wells and gets 30 million cubic meters
of hot water annually. Three surface geothermal pools alone
provide enough water for central heating for 3 million sq.m. of
residential housing.
</P>
<P>
This has allowed the Tanggu District to shut down 581 boilers
and 500 chimneys, and at least 100,000 people are benefiting from
the geothermal energy.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin has branched out in its use of geothermal energy, from
central heating and industrial use to greenhouses, aquatic
products, therapeutic uses, mineral water, and scientific
research.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980416.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Economy Gloomy: Finance Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has
painted a gloomy picture of the country's economy as it struggles
to find a medium and long-term solution to economic and social
problems.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Finance Minister Simeon Nyachae said Wednesday that
Kenya's economy has slowed down significantly partly as a result
of fiscal imbalances which the government has experienced over
the years, the East African Standard reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The current slowdown in the economy, the high interest rates
that discouraged investments in the real sector, the large volume
of short term government debt and the dilapidated infrastructure
are big challenges to the east African state, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The current large stock of 91-day Treasury bills, which
necessitated a roll-over every week, make it difficult to reduce
interest rates from the current high levels. The situation has
been exacerbated by the decline in external receipts," said the
minister.
</P>
<P>
At the current yields on Treasury bills, the government would
pay 31 billion Shillings (521 million U.S. Dollars) of its
ordinary revenue on domestic debt interest payments in the
1997/98 fiscal year, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Consequently, budget for operations and maintenance will
continue to decline thereby inhibiting delivery of public
services. In short, public servants continue to be paid but are
not provided with the tools to render services which the public
expects," he said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the total wage bill should be reduced as a
proportion of both government revenue and the gross domestic
product.
</P>
<P>
"It is important for Kenyans to understand its implications on
both the quality and quantity of public services together with
its impact on the economy," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
