<HEADLINE> Korean Talks Re-open Without Tangible Results </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Negotiators for North and South
Korea adjourned again here this morning after a two-hour
closed-door session which showed no sign of tangible results
following Wednesday's break.
</P>
<P>
"We had a serious meeting today," said Chun Kum Chul, head of
the delegation of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea
(DPRK), but he declined to comment on any progress.
</P>
<P>
"The time for the next round of talks will be considered and
fixed after further contacts," Chun said.
</P>
<P>
So far, the delegation of the Republic of Korea (ROK) has not
made any comment on the morning session. But they are scheduled to
leave Beijing on Saturday, one source said.
</P>
<P>
Local observers say it is still too early to say what would
really come out of further talks.
</P>
<P>
This working-level morning session opened at 10:05 and ended at
12:05, with the head delegate and one member from each side in
attendance at a local hotel where talks started last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
A DPRK delegate was quoted as saying his delegation would not
be leaving even when the talks conclude. The DPRK insists that the
fertilizer aid issue should be tackled first, a source said.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, both sides agreed to stay for another two days
after the unsuccessful third round of full meetings, which failed
to reach agreement on terms for the ROK's supply of fertilizer aid
to the DPRK.
</P>
<P>
Both sides stayed in contact Thursday, waiting for the other
side to take the first step to re-start the talks. But concessions
failed to come from either side.
</P>
<P>
These are the first direct talks between the two governments in
four years. 
</P>
