<HEADLINE> Chinese State Councillor Confers with Thai Deputy Prime Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Chinese State Councillor Wu Yi
reiterated today that China will not seek entry into the World
Trade Organization (WTO) if it has to sacrifice its own
fundamental interests.
</P>
<P>
Wu made the remark this morning in talks with Supachai
Panitchpakdi, deputy prime minister and minister of Commerce of
Thailand who is here as Wu's guest.
</P>
<P>
Supachai briefed Wu on Thailand's domestic economic situation,
hoping to further bilateral exchanges and cooperation in various
fields, including trade.
</P>
<P>
He said that Thailand actively supports China's early entry
into the WTO, for which Wu expressed her appreciation.
</P>
<P>
Wu told Supachai that China, as a responsible member of the
international community, will spare no effort to help Southeast
Asian nations which have suffered from the financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
She went on to say that Chinese government has taken part in the
package financial assistance program sponsored by the
International Monetary Fund (IMF), which is unprecedented for
China to participate in such a program under an international and
regional framework.
</P>
<P>
Among IMF's total 17.2 billion U.S. dollars in assistance,
Chinese offer is second only to that of the United States and
Japan, and higher than any other western countries, Wu said.
</P>
<P>
She said the Chinese government has already provided the Thai
government with one billion U.S. dollars in loans, and that
Thailand is the only country receiving such bilateral assistance
from China since the outbreak of the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Wu stressed that China has made a commitment not to devalue its
currency -- Renminbi -- and supports the stability of the Hong
Kong dollar, and it will continue to do so unswervingly even if
China suffers a lot.
</P>
<P>
Expressing a deep sympathy with Southeast Asian nations,
including Thailand, and an admiration for the Thai people's
efforts to overcome their difficulties, Wu said that China, as a
friendly neighbor of Thailand, all along has been concerned about
Thailand's difficulties and will exert substantial efforts to help
Thailand out of its difficulties at an early date.
</P>
<P>
Both sides also exchanged opinions on further strengthening
bilateral economic and trade cooperation under the current
conditions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
