<HEADLINE> New Chinese Economic Minister Comments On Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Sheng Huaren, the
newly-appointed State Economic and Trade Commission minister says
he is quite certain that China can reach its goal of 11-percent
growth in industrial production this year, "China Economic Times"
reports today.
</P>
<P>
China should stick to the tasks of the State Council for 1998
in working for an eight-percent increase in economic growth and
that the industrial growth should be 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
Based on the first quarter results, Sheng said, industrial
growth rate in the period is likely to be 8.2 percent, lower than
the same period of last year, although this has not been
officially announced.
</P>
<P>
The economist-minister says that 8.2-percent growth is normal
for the first quarter and the growth is expected to reach 11
percent in the second quarter, and stay around 12 percent in the
third and fourth quarters. In this way, the annual goal of
11-percent increase can be reached, Sheng said.
</P>
<P>
However, a special effort will be made in four areas:
</P>
<P>
-- State fixed assets investment will be increased to stimulate
consumer spending and the rural market, which is expected to be
much larger than urban market.
</P>
<P>
-- The state should increase exports, especially of light
industry, textile, machinery, electronics, and chemical products
in spite of the adverse effects of the Asian financial crisis in
the latter half of last year.
</P>
<P>
-- Priority will be given to technological improvements and to
product mix to meet domestic and international market needs.
</P>
<P>
-- The State Economic and Trade Commission should cooperate
with finance departments to provide enterprises with good
performance records with adequate funds for expansion of
production and exports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
