<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Governmental Debt Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government's total
domestic debt rose to 149.6 billion Shillings (2.514 billion U.S.
Dollars) at the end of February from 148.9 billion Shillings at
the end of January, the Central Bank of Kenya (CBK) says.
</P>
<P>
The CBK monthly report for April#,quoted by Thursday's East
African Standard newspaper, said domestic debt represented 23.2
percent of GDP and comprised mainly government securities,
Treasury bills, Treasury bonds and long term stock.
</P>
<P>
Government's total domestic debt stood at 130.8 billion
Shillings at the end of the 1996/97 fiscal year ending in June
1997, it said.
</P>
<P>
Of the outstanding goverrnment securities, Treasury bills
accounted for 119.7 billion Shillings or 72.5 percent of GDP,
down from 121.2 billion Shillings at the end of January.
</P>
<P>
The banking sector continued to be the biggest holder of
treasury bills, accounting for 44.4 billion Shillings worth.
</P>
<P>
The CBK held 16.2 billion Shillings of which 16 billion
Shillings was acquired through repurchase agreements "for the
purpose of conducting monetary policy" and the remaining 0.2
percent was held in rediscounted bills, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Money supply growth decelerated to a 5.8 percent year-on-year
rise in February 1998 from 9.8 percent in January and compared to
17.4 percent in February 1997.
</P>
<P>
The slowdown was supported by the decline in net foreign
assets of the banking system as net domestic assets increased.
</P>
<P>
"The monetary contraction was above the expectation with the
February money stock of 293.6 billion Shillings falling below the
295.7 billion Shillings target," said the report.
</P>
<P>
"This is consistent with the objective of monetary policy in
the year to June 1998 which is to limit the growth in money
supply to not more than 8.3 percent in order to achieve low and
stable inflation," the report said.
</P>
<P>
It said that the government collected 111.9 billion Shillings
in revenue from domestic sources in the first eight months of
fiscal year 1997/98 (July/June)#,compared to 94.8 billion
Shillings in the same period the previous year.
</P>
<P>
"The government received a further 3.5 billion Shillings in
the form of external grants, which was a 1.2 billion Shillings
decline... and 0.8 billion Shillings below target," it said.
</P>
<P>
The government's net borrowing from the Central Bank for the
fiscal year up to February amounted to 12.6 billion Shillings
compared to 4.0 billion Shillings in the same period last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
