<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Taking a Closer Look at Reasons for Yellow River's Dryness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Five journalists from China's
Central TV Station and the Economic Daily began a three-month
journey on Wednesday to study the impact of drying up of lower
reaches of the Yellow River, today's "Economic Daily" reports.
</P>
<P>
A ceremony was held in Beijing yesterday to mark the start of
the expedition. The journalists will travel from the river's
estuary in Shandong Province, in the east, to its source in
Qinghai Province in the northwest.
</P>
<P>
Jiang Chunyun, vice-chairman of the National People's Congress
Standing Committee, Chen Junsheng, vice-chairman of the Chinese
People's Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC) National
Committee, and Niu Maosheng, Water Resources minister, were
present for the event.
</P>
<P>
The Yellow River wanders for 5,464 km across China from its
source in the Bayanhar Mountains in Qinghai and flows east through
nine provinces and autonomous regions, emptying into the sea in
Shandong.
</P>
<P>
The river has been drying up more frequently in certain spots
and for longer periods of time since the first stoppage was
reported in the lower reaches in 1972, and then, in 1997, it
stopped flowing for 272 days.
</P>
<P>
The interrupted flow is largely blamed on insufficient water
at the source, a sharp increase in water consumption, a serious
waste of water in daily use, a lack of management, and pollution.
</P>
<P>
It has also caused serious problems for the country. The lower
reaches in Shandong lost more than 13 billion yuan in business and
3.6 million people had difficulties getting drinking water in
1997, according to local reports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980416.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Gets Large Export Deal With Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 16 (Xinhua) -- A ship loaded with equipment for
China's largest commercial venture outside the country, the Tehran
Underground Railway Project, left the port of Shanghai on
Wednesday for Iran.
</P>
<P>
The first load of equipment includes six locomotives, each
weighting 88 tons, and 24 double-decker shuttle buses.
</P>
<P>
The project is expected to cost 550 million US dollars and is
the largest construction project in Iran over recent decades. It
has two parts: underground railway lines and a suburban
electrified railway line that are expected to help solve the
transportation problem from Tehran to a suburban area with a
million people.
</P>
<P>
The first phase, the 43-km suburban electrified railway line,
is planned to be completed in late 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
