<DOCNO> XIE19980416.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNG Rebels Boycott Meeting Organized by Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Prominent Bougainville rebel
leaders have boycotted a meeting organized by their political
figurehead Francis Ona in an indication of a widening split in the
leadership of the secessionists in the Bougainville island, Papua
New Guinea (PNG).
</P>
<P>
The meeting of Bougainville chiefs and politicians at Pakia
Village in the island's center entered its second day Thursday
without the presence of two key rebel figures, Joseph Kabui and
military commander Sam Kauona, the Australian Associated Press
reported.
</P>
<P>
The gathering is seen as an attempt by Ona to involve himself
in the current peace process on the Pacific island which has been
wrecked by a 10-year war for independence from PNG, the wire
service said.
</P>
<P>
The reclusive Ona has excluded himself from ongoing peace talks
between the warring factions which paved the way for a ceasefire
due to start next month, it said.
</P>
<P>
Kabui, vice-president of the rebel's political arm, issued a
statement overnight saying that prominent rebel leaders wanted to
talk to Ona before the Pakia gathering.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman from Ona's office near Pakia said on Thursday that
the meeting was intended as a unifying exercise for
Bougainvillians.
</P>
<P>
Despite the rift, Kabui said that Ona was still the paramount
political leader of the rebels, and that there was no attempt to
exclude him from the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Ona's intransigency has been a stumbling block to previous
attempts to end the secessionist crisis, with his repeated refusal
to take part in other peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Some observers see the Pakia meeting as a belated attempt by
Ona to shore up his diminishing leadership.
</P>
<P>
Pakia is located near the giant Paguna copper-mine which
triggered the secessionist crisis a decade ago after landowner and
royalty disputes and accusations of environmental damage.
</P>
<P>
The mine is mainly owned by Australian company RTZ-CRA.
</P>
<P>
The rebels have harbored mistrust of the Australian government,
which trained and equipped PNG's military during the conflict in
which an estimated 15,000 people have died, the Australian wire
service said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
