<DOCNO> XIE19980416.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Preparing To Face Serious Flood Battle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 16 (Xinhua) -- China is involved in a race
against time to repair its water conservation facilities, in
anticipation of bigger flooding than usual this year.
</P>
<P>
Meteorologists say that China could have unprecedented
flooding, with rain covering a wider area and heavy rainfalls in
the Yangtze River Valley and upper reaches of the Yellow River
this summer.
</P>
<P>
The flood season got off to a start in January, two months
earlier than usual, causing flooding in Jiangxi, Hunan, Fujian,
and Guangdong provinces, according to Zhu Dengquan, vice-minister
of water resources, who spoke with Xinhua recently.
</P>
<P>
In early March, heavy rains pushed water levels in the middle
and lower reaches of the Yangtze and on Taihu Lake up, causing the
third biggest flood in the history of the Ganjiang River, and
record flooding on the Xiangjiang and Minjiang rivers, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Ganjiang and Xiangjiang are branches of the Yangtze and the
Minjiang is mainly in Fujian Province.
</P>
<P>
The ministry and the State Flood and Drought Control HQ are
urging disaster-prone areas to increase preparation, Zhu said, and
the two will soon send flood-control experts for a look at flood
prevention efforts in the Yellow, Huaihe and Haihe river
valleys. One team, led by Vice-minister Zhou Wenzhi, has already
returned to Beijing from the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
While the south is preparing to deal with flooding, the north
is suffering from a serious drought that has affected planting in
the Northeast and in the eastern part of Inner Mongolia, the
vice-minister said.
</P>
<P>
There has been much less rainfall than usual this year in the
North, with about 20 million ha of farmland hit by drought in
February, Zhu said. The Yellow River has dried up six times so far
this year, and the lower reaches had no flow for a total of 70
days, he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister and the State Flood and Drought Control
Headquarters have sent 12 teams to the hardest-hit areas to
coordinate drought-relief efforts.
</P>
<P>
Niu Maosheng, the water resources minister, says that northern
China, and Sichuan Province and the city of Chongqing in the
Southwest have spent a great deal of money digging wells and
canals to bring water from rivers and encouraging the use of
water-saving irrigation technology.  
</P>
</TEXT>
