<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Signs, Then Appeals Arts Return Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
signed Wednesday a law banning the return to Germany of cultural
treasures looted by the Soviet army in World War II -- but
immediately appealed against it to the Constitutional Court.
</P>
<P>
The ITAR-Tass News Agency said Yeltsin argued in the passage of
the so-called trophy art bill that it "directly violates both the
constitution of the Russian Federation and the country's
international obligations."
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin argued that the law does not differentiate between
German art works and those seized by the Nazis from other
countries and individuals in Europe.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin said the signing of the bill, which is required by the
constitutional court, would complicate Russia's relations with
certain countries. It would also make it difficult for Russia to
ask for the return of its own art treasures looted by Nazi
Germany, which outnumbered the arts works taken by Russia.
</P>
<P>
Sergei Shakhrai, Yeltsin's representative at the Constitutional
Court, explained a few days ago that according to Russian
constitution, when a Russian law had provisions contradictory with
international treaties signed by Russia, the national law had to
follow the international law.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin vetoed the bill in March 1997, but was overridden by
both houses of parliament. He then refused to sign.
</P>
<P>
The Constitutional Court ruled in early April that the
president must sign the bill before he can file an appeal
challenging the constitutionality of the new law.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that treasures taken by the Soviet army during
World War II amounted to 200,000 pieces including books,
paintings, sculptures, coins and medals and other art works. But
the number of art works seized by Nazi Germany from Russia totaled
500,000 pieces.
</P>
<P>
The return of looted art has always been a thorny issue
between the two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980416.0249 </DOCNO>
