<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Half Foreign Investment Proposals not Implemented </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Nearly half of the 205 foreign
investment proposals registered with Bangladesh's Board of
Investment (BOI) since July 1996 have not made any progress, a
press report said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A recent BOI survey revealed that there was no physical
progress in implementing 46 percent, or 94 of the 205 proposals
with a total estimated investment of 1,807 million U.S. dollars,
The Financial Express daily reported, quoting BOI officials.
</P>
<P>
Only 157 million dollars, or about 9 percent of the proposed
foreign investment, have been made in 38 projects which have
already started production, they said. These projects are mainly
engaged in the service sector, textiles and food processing.
</P>
<P>
Nine other projects involving 190 million dollars will go into
production soon, and 64 proposals with an estimated investment of
474 million dollars are under different stages of implementation.
</P>
<P>
Japan tops the list of the projects implemented with an
investment of 68 million dollars, followed by Britain and
Singapore with 33 million dollars of investment each.
</P>
<P>
BOI officials attributed the low rate of implementation to
non-availability of industrial plots with ready-made
infrastructure facilities and utility services, non-availability
of bank loans, cumbersome customs and bureaucratic procedures,
problems at the port, litigation between local and foreign
partners, corruption and unnecessary documentation process.
</P>
<P>
Inadequate and erratic supply of power and interference of the
musclemen also create unwanted obstacles in implementing the
projects, and the recent economic crisis in neighboring Southeast
Asian countries may have also hindered foreign investment in
Bangladesh, they said.
</P>
<P>
The officials nonetheless termed the overall trend of foreign
investment as positive in the country, saying that the problems of
the stalled projects would be resolved gradually. The BOI have
held meetings with foreign investors to solve their problems, they
said.
</P>
<P>
The BOI registered a total of 2,137 projects with a proposed
investment of 3,404 million dollars between July 1996, when the
present government was formed, and December 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
