<HEADLINE> Canada Welcomes Brazil's Treaty Ratification </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian government Wednesday
welcomed Brazil's ratification of a treaty on the transfer of
criminals in jail.
</P>
<P>
The two countries are expected to exchange the instruments of
ratification this week.
</P>
<P>
The treaty, which was signed between the two countries six
years ago, will come into force 30 days after the exchange, a
government news release said.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian-Brazilian treaty is designed to "advance the
rehabilitation of Canadian and Brazilian offenders by allowing
them better contact with families and friends, and to facilitate
their eventual reintegration into society at home," said Canadian
Foreign Minister Lloyd Axworthy.
</P>
<P>
There are some 1,500 Canadians in jails around the world, with
seven of them in Brazil, the release said.
</P>
<P>
Canada has had such treaties with Bolivia, Egypt, France,
Mexico, Morocco, Peru, Thailand, the United States and Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
These treaties allow criminals to serve their sentences closer
to their families in their own countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
