<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Privatization Program Gets Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lanka's privatization
program is showing development with 59.7 million U.S. dollars
being realized during the first quarter of this year, the official
News Daily reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A sum of 371 million dollars in 1997 was realized from 78.33
million dollars in 1996 and 49.15 million dollars in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The biggest privatization deal so far has been national carrier
Air Lanka which put its 40 percent for the United Arab Emirates
Airlines. An agreement for this was signed here at the end of
last month.
</P>
<P>
The Sri Lanka's privatization program was launched in 1978 to
accelerate economic development in the country.
</P>
<P>
This was to be done through improvement in efficiency and
competitiveness in the national economy, acquisition of new
technology and expertise and open access to international markets
and enhance capital formation, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Additionally, the divestiture of state-owned enterprises has
reduced government expenditure through the reduction in transfers
to set off large losses and financial capital expenditure which
otherwise would have suffered due to lack of funds.
</P>
<P>
This enables the government to channel more resources to other
development activities and poverty alleviation and social welfare.
</P>
<P>
Several more ventures have been lined up for this year. They
include two farms, the licensing of the import of lubricants,
stakes in several plantation companies as well as a few other
state ventures and the restructuring of the giant Pugoda Textile
Mill.
</P>
<P>
The paper added that the overall program in 1998 will aim at
the minimizing of the benefits of the government shareholding of
already privatized public enterprises through asset management
mechanisms to secure high dividends and other forms of income to
the government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
