<DOCNO> XIE19980416.0268 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Calls for Concerted Fight Against Drugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The world is "at the
crossroads" in dealing with the drug problem, the U.N. Under
Secretary General for Drug Control, Pino Arlacchi, said on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Countries may continue "taking one step forwards for every two
steps back," or they may recognize that drug control requires a
global solution, the official said in a speech at the National
Press Club here.
</P>
<P>
The official said the U.N. drug control program "looks to the
United States" for financial and intellectual resources in a
coordinated international effort against production, trafficking,
distribution and demand of drugs.
</P>
<P>
"The United States remains a key player in our new global
strategy to eliminate the production and use of illegal drugs by
the year 2008," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The United States is a particularly interesting case because
it is both a consumer and a producer country," he said. "The
United States remains the world's main consumer market for illegal
drugs."
</P>
<P>
According to the U.N. program, in 1993 Americans spent 48.3
billion dollars on cocaine, heroin and cannabis. In an average
month in 1994, 15 million Americans used illicit drugs, 10 million
used cannabis, and 1.4 million used cocaine.
</P>
<P>
"UNDCP estimates that one-fourth of the cannabis consumed in
this country is grown domestically," Arlacchi said. "The illicit
manufacture of drugs is also widespread, particularly
methamphetamines, and to a lesser extent, hallucinogens,
depressants, cocaine and opiates."
</P>
<P>
However, "real improvement has been made over the past decade,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"The amount of money spent on drug consumption is 23 percent
less today than it was in 1988, and the number of Americans who
use cocaine every month is down a striking 80 percent from the
estimated 5.7 million who used the drug every month in 1985,"
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
