<DOCNO> XIE19980416.0269 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Reaffirms Commitment to Vienna Convention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 15 (Xinhua) -- A day after Virginia executed
a Paraguayan man, the United States on Wednesday reaffirmed its
commitment to the Vienna Convention that guarantees consular
access.
</P>
<P>
United States Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said the
U.S. remained committed to the principle of consular protection
for foreigners accused of crimes.
</P>
<P>
Albright, speaking during a stop-over in Miami on her way to a
weekend Summit of the Americas in Santiago, Chile, said the
executed man, Angel Francisco Breard had received a fair trial.
</P>
<P>
But she said the U.S. stood by conventions over consular help
and insisted on the same rights for its own citizens.
</P>
<P>
"We have made very clear that it is essential any foreign
national who is arrested for any reason...is told immediately that
he or she is entitled to be in touch with their consul," she said.
</P>
<P>
Breard, 32, was executed Tuesday for a 1992 murder of an
American woman, despite requests for a delay from International
Court of Justice in the Hague because the Paraguayan's right to
notify his government was not complied with.
</P>
<P>
The local authorities in the Washington suburb of Arlington
failed to inform Breard of his right to consular help from his
homeland, as required by the Vienna Convention on Consular
Relations.
</P>
<P>
Paraguay has reportedly accused the United States of having a
double standard on human rights after the execution went ahead
despite the World Court ruling.
</P>
<P>
U.S. State Department spokesman James Rubin told reporters on
Wednesday that Albright recently sent governors of the 50 states a
booklet entitled "Consular Notification and Access" explaining
U.S. obligations under the treaty.
</P>
<P>
Albright asked Virginia Governor James Gilmore to stay the
execution for the sake of Americans traveling abroad.
</P>
<P>
The United States relies on the Vienna convention, which has
been signed by more than 130 countries including the U.S., when
Americans get into trouble abroad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
