<HEADLINE> Greece Backs Bulgaria for EU, NATO Memberships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, April 15 (Xinhua) - Greece has voiced its support for
Bulgaria's plan to join the European Union and the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
In a joint press conference on Wednesday with his Bulgarian
counterpart Ivan Kostov, Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis said
the EU should embrace all European countries. He added that
Bulgaria's participation in the EU's expansion is a key factor for
the new stage of Bulgarian-Greek relations that started in 1989.
</P>
<P>
He believes bilateral relations will improve in quality based
on European standards and rules.
</P>
<P>
NATO's expansion should go further and the participation of the
Balkan countries in the pact will guarantee regional security,
said the Greek prime minister, who arrived here Tuesday for a
two-day visit.
</P>
<P>
He said the Balkans need a policy of cooperation to promote
peace and stability in the region. "We are against the creation of
axes and groups that create demarcation lines," said Simitis.
</P>
<P>
Kostov said the two sides share identical views on the regional
situation. "I am happy we stand together in our assessment of the
future and in the will to solve the Kosovo issue and
perform our roles as a major factor of stability in the Balkans."
</P>
<P>
During Simitis's visit, the two sides discussed the
construction of new motorways through the Roudozem-Xanthe, Gotse
Delchev-Drama and Kurdjali-Komotini border crossings.
</P>
<P>
The two sides promised that the ratification of a 1991 bilateral
accord on avoidance of double taxation would be stepped up, and a
separate protocol would be signed on transport-related questions
that Bulgaria has raised.
</P>
<P>
The two countries also agreed to promote cooperation between
the interior ministries in combating organized crime, terrorism
and the illegal transportation of drugs and arms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
