<HEADLINE> Italy Prepares For Three-Year Economic Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The Italian government Wednesday
held two crucial meetings on its new three-year economic plan in
preparation for its formal launch on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The 1999-2001 document was submitted for discussion to
parliamentary leaders and union confederations.
</P>
<P>
The economic policy blueprint contains plans for the creation
of 700,000 jobs, said the Democratic Left floor leader Fabio
Mussi, after one of the meetings.
</P>
<P>
He said unemployment would fall by 0.7 percent in 1999, 0.9
percent in 2000 and one percent in 2001, putting it at under 10
percent at the end of the three years.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, the public debt would also fall to under 100
percent of GDP by 2003 so that Italy could meet the convergence
criteria for the European single currency.
</P>
<P>
These figures are closely associated with a predicted rise in
GDP of 2.7 percent in 1999, three percent in 2000 and 2.9 percent
in 2001. 
</P>
