<HEADLINE> OSCE Chief Visits Kazakstan to Boost Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Poland and the OSCE hope the
five Caspian Sea countries will resolve their dispute over the
legal status of the sea peacefully and reach an agreement as soon
as possible, Polish Foreign Minister Bronislaw Geremek said here
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Geremek, current chairman of the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe, told a joint press conference held with his
Kazak counterpart Kasymzhomart Tokayev that the countries on the
Caspian Sea coast, Russia, Kazakstan, Turkmenistan, Iran and
Azerbaijan, must settle the problem and sign a protocol on
dividing or sharing the sea and its resources as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Tokayev said Kazakstan and Russia have already reached a
consensus and will ink an agreement in the near future. He
believes the Caspian nations can also resolve their disputes and
come to an agreement.
</P>
<P>
The Polish foreign minister, who arrived here Tuesday evening,
also met Kazak President Nursultan Nazarbayev on Wednesday and
discussed the OSCE plan for central Asia.
</P>
<P>
Nazarbayev said as an OSCE member, Kazakstan hopes to
strengthen cooperation with the organization. The Kazak president
also hoped that the OSCE could play a role in maintaining
stability in central Asia. 
</P>
