<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wandering Chinese River In Loess Plateau Brought Under Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The Wuding ('Unfixed') River in the
Loess Plateau of northwest China has finally been brought under
control and people have taken to calling it the "Yongding"
(Eternally Still).
</P>
<P>
Long ago, the river, which runs by the Muus Desert in the
northern part of Shaanxi Province, had a fertile valley with
flocks of sheep wandering here and there. But wars and unchecked
logging left the area desolate. This caused the river to wander
more, bringing in a large amount of silt and desert, a condition
that then plagued the people for centuries.
</P>
<P>
In the early 1950s, forest and grass covered a mere 1.8 percent
of the area. But, in the 1980s, the government started a campaign
to put the river under control, with a shelter-belt project and a
40,000-hectare irrigation project in sandy areas.
</P>
<P>
The past five years have been the period of greatest success in
this, with 110,000 hectares of land improved, and a reduction of
6.27 million tons of silt annually. In addition, per-capita income
of farmers went up from 530 yuan to 1,400 yuan.
</P>
<P>
The local people now work on terraced fields in the watershed
area and most have gotten involved in some sort of cottage
industry or other. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
