<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> G7 Urges Japan to Take Effective Measures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Financial leaders of the Group
of Seven industrial nations on Wednesday urged Japan to take
"effective fiscal measures and structural reforms" to achieve a
strong economy.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued after their meeting in Washington, which was
attended by finance ministers and bank governors of France,
Britain, Canada, Italy, the United States, Japan and Germany, said
Japan had taken positive steps to stimulate its economy.
</P>
<P>
However, it said, "The challenges facing Japan are serious and
have intensified in recent months."
</P>
<P>
The Japanese yen has depreciated so sharply that in March it
reached its lowest value against the U.S. dollar since 1992, and
the International Monetary Fund (IMF) forecasts that Japan's
output growth will be zero this year.
</P>
<P>
The financial leaders said they would cooperate in foreign
exchange markets and try to prevent excessive currency falls.
</P>
<P>
But they did not discuss the possibility of joint action in
currency markets to prop up the yen, United States Treasury
Secretary Robert Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news briefing after the G7 meeting, Rubin said
that the world was still waiting for Japan to provide more details
about its plans to stimulate its ailing economy.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated his support for a strong dollar, but also noted
that he continued to share Japan's concern over the excessively
weak yen.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said the G7 was eager to see quick action by Japan to
boost its economy after Tokyo announced a series of fiscal
stimulus measures last week.
</P>
<P>
"The world still hasn't seen the details," he said. "The market
will provide an evaluation as to whether that program is
sufficient."
</P>
<P>
Rubin added that Japan gave no sign of any plans to continue
intervening in currency markets on behalf of the yen.
</P>
<P>
The G-7 financial leaders believed the measures announced by
the Japanese government last month would help correct the
excessive weakness of the yen.
</P>
<P>
"We emphasized that it is important to avoid excessive
depreciation where this could exacerbate large external
imbalances. In light of this, we support appropriate steps by
Japan aimed at stimulating domestic demand-led growth and reducing
external imbalances, thus also correcting the excessive
depreciation of the yen," they said.
</P>
<P>
"What is crucial (for Japan) is to implement quickly a strong
program of effective fiscal confidence," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Japan was the focus of the meeting, which is part of the spring
meetings of the IMF and the World Bank. It will be followed by a
meeting in England next month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980416.0287 </DOCNO>
