<HEADLINE> Progress Made on China's WTO Admission: US Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 15 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Trade Representative
Charlene Barshefsky said here Wednesday that important progress
has been made regarding China's access to the World Trade
Organization(WTO), but some issues remain to be solved.
</P>
<P>
"I think we've made progress with China, and I think the
progress, from time to time, would be what I would consider to be
important progress with China on this," she told a gathering at
the Institute for International Economics Conference.
</P>
<P>
The official did not elaborate. It was reported earlier that
she would go to Beijing probably by the end of this month to
continue the tough negotiations with China.
</P>
<P>
China has declared several tariff cuts in recent years to
pave its way to the WTO, but the United States still feels they are
insufficient.
</P>
<P>
Barshefsky reaffirmed that the United States would welcome
China to the global trade organization, but certain requirements
must be met.
</P>
<P>
"We would like to see China's entry into the WTO. We think it's
important for China; we think it's important for the WTO; we think
it's very important for the United States; but only, only on the
basis of commercially meaningful commitments," she said.
</P>
<P>
Washington is pushing for further opening of the Chinese
market, especially the service sector. China, still a developing
country, has committed itself to the WTO rules, but insists that
changes should be a gradual process.
</P>
<P>
"Until that can be accomplished, we can't seriously entertain
the admission of any country -- any new country into the WTO," the
U.S. official said, giving little hope for a breakthrough in
Sino-U.S. negotiations.
</P>
<P>
As President Bill Clinton will visit China in late June, it is
speculated that the two sides might try to remove the obstacles
for China's WTO membership. However, it may be too early to
predict if a final settlement could be reached prior to or during
President Clinton's China trip.
</P>
<P>
The United States, as Barshefsky said, is "looking at a range
of market access issues, whether tariffs, non-tariff barriers,
services trade, agriculture trade, industrial goods, and so on and
so forth."
</P>
<P>
"We see a regime that we believe is intent on reform; we would
like to capture that spirit in connection with the WTO, but that
decision ultimately is only for China to make," she said.
</P>
<P>
However, China complained that Washington lacks adequate and
accurate understanding of China's situation, and its conditions
for WTO admission are too harsh to accept for a developing country
like China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980416.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
