<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese College Students Think Love Basis of Successful Marriage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 16 (Xinhua) -- A recent study has shown that
nearly eight out of ten Chinese college students believe that a
marriage should be based on love, and about 90 percent think that
feelings are very important in choosing a spouse or boyfriend or
girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
The figures show that China's younger generation has adopted a
more modern and idealistic view of marriage as the country
undergoes rapid economic and social changes, according to Lu
Shizhen, a scholar of the China Youth Political College, who
conducted the survey of 500 students in 9 of Beijing's colleges.
</P>
<P>
Traditional emphasis on social and economic status in choosing
a husband or wife seems to hold little importance for the college
students, according to the survey, and as many as 60.8 percent
expressed indifference to family background, while 74.6 percent
attached much importance to moral character and 65.8 percent to
temperament.
</P>
<P>
With livelihood no longer a major issue in family life, Lu
says, people tend to look more for emotional fulfillment in a
family, something that gets added force from increasing pressures
on people living in an increasingly competitive and indifferent
society.
</P>
<P>
The survey also suggests that Chinese college students have
adopted a more liberal attitude toward sex since 13.4 percent
admitted having had some sexual experience, while 69.1 percent
thought that pre-marital co-habitation or pre-marital sex were
acceptable. Male students tend to have more liberal view than
female ones.
</P>
<P>
As for placing importance on occupation and income in a
marriage, female students' belief in them was 9.3 percentage
points higher than for male students in the former an 8.1
percentage points higher in the latter.
</P>
<P>
This seems to indicate that men are still expected to be the
major source of support of a marriage and family, which is in line
with traditional thinking, Lu says, and he expects that in future
families in China will be a blend of both the modern and the
traditional.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980416.0293 </DOCNO>
