<HEADLINE> Car Exhaust Turns Out A Major Concern for Chinese Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Since a car is no longer a luxury
for many Chinese, they have been living in cities choked by
automobile's harmful exhaust fumes. While the government
departments are committing greater efforts to curb the pollution,
said today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing municipal government has carried out spot-checks on
automobiles on the road since early this month. Those vehicles
that exceed State emission control limits must get catalytic
converters installed at designated fitting stations.
</P>
<P>
Now, 1.2 million vehicles in the city have been using lead-free
petrol as another measure to curb exhaust fume
pollution. Guangzhou, capital of south China's Guangdong Province,
has banned the sale and use of leaded petrol.
</P>
<P>
China now totals 12 million automobiles. Guangzhou has one
million cars and Shanghai 470,000. They discharge 10 million tons
of carbon monoxide and one million tons of nitrogen oxide
annually, according to Shen Dixin, an environmental expert with
the National Ecological Research Center.
</P>
<P>
There are now more spot checks on automobile emissions and more
than 30 cities in the country have been publicizing weekly reports
on their air quality through the media.
</P>
<P>
As in the capital, monitoring showed the content of carbon
monoxide in the air of 30 streets in the downtown area within the
Third Ring Road of Beijing exceeded the State standards by 100
percent.
</P>
<P>
Experts urged the exact amount of different air pollutants
contributing to atmospheric contamination should be measured to
provide scientific data. Meanwhile, cars and light-duty vehicles
which are used in big cities in large numbers are the focus of the
emission control studies, said officials from the government
departments in charge of car manufacturing industries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980416.0295 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Be World's 2nd Biggest PC Market, Intel Official Predicts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Intel Corp., the leading
international computer chip supplier, estimates that China will
become the world's second-largest market for personal computers
(PC) early next century, following the United States.
</P>
<P>
By 2000, China's PC sales may surpass 200 billion yuan,
according to predictions made by an Intel representative in
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Official figures show that, in 1997, the country's computer
sales topped 130 billion yuan, including 41.5 billion yuan from PC
buyers. A total of 3.5 million PCs were sold in the domestic
market.
</P>
<P>
Local experts say China's computer market remains in a
"rapid-growth" period, while the PC market is the most active part
and faces fierce competition among dealers.
</P>
<P>
The Intel representative told Xinhua that his company is
confident of its prospects in China's PC market as the country has
launched a series of national programs to popularize computers,
especially PCs, in all economic and industrial fields.
</P>
<P>
One of the two Intel labs in Asia is located in Shanghai, he
said. This year, the U.S. company has sponsored a series of
seminars to help small- and medium-sized firms learn more about the
use of computer technology.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
