<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Foreign Debts Down to 133.7b US Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's total foreign debts
Dropped from 136.1 billion U.S. dollars at the end of December
last year to 133.7 billion dollars at the end of January this
year, Bank Indonesia has said.
</P>
<P>
A press statement issued Wednesday by the central bank said the
debt comprises government debts of 53.5 billion dollars and
private sector debts of 80.2 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The statement said all of the government's foreign debts are
long term, while the private sector's debt consists of 72.8
billion dollars in the form of loans, and 7.4 billion dollars in
forms of commercial papers.
</P>
<P>
It said short-term debts amounted to 15.6 billion dollars,
where 9.6 billion dollars were in the form of loans and 6 billion
dollars in the form of commercial paper.
</P>
<P>
Bank Indonesia also announced Wednesday it had issued a
circular on a requirement to report any foreign loan to the bank.
</P>
<P>
It said that all commercial foreign loans of any amount have to
be reported to the central bank. "Companies that have never
reported their foreign loans before are required to report their
loans by April 30, 1998," it said.
</P>
<P>
If companies are late with the report, they will be fined
500,000 rupiah (about 65 U.S. dollars) per week after the
deadline, the circular added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
