<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0200 GMT April 16 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The Group of Seven industrial countries agreed
here Wednesday to cooperate in foreign exchange markets and try to
prevent excessive currency falls, urging Japan to "quickly" take
effective measures and structural reforms.
</P>
<P>
Financial leaders of the group said in a statement issued after
their meeting, which was attended by finance ministers and bank
governors from France, Britain, Canada, Italy, the U.S., Japan and
Germany, that Japan had taken positive steps to stimulate its
economy.
</P>
<P>
The yen depreciated sharply for the past months and reached its
lowest level in March against the dollar since early 1992, and the
International Monetary Fund projected Japan's economy growth in
1998 at zero. (US-G-7)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The Group 24 developing nations Wednesday urged
the International Monetary Fund (IMF), the World Bank and major
industrial countries to accelerate the pace of debt relief to
countries undergoing economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
The G-24 developing countries also said in a communique that it
wants a task force of industrial and developing countries to
review the ability of these institutions to "prevent and to
respond in a timely and effective manner to crises induced by
large-scale capital movements."
</P>
<P>
The communique was issued after its 59th meeting concluded
Wednesday afternoon in Washington. (G24-Communique)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Acting Russian Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko told a
briefing here on Wednesday that all proposals on candidates for
positions in the Cabinet will be considered attentively.
</P>
<P>
However, it does not guarantee that all candidates will be
appointed, although "there have been some interesting
suggestions," Kiriyenko said.
</P>
<P>
The acting premier said his duty is to present an economic
program and fill it with concrete content, and the Duma would vote
on an economic program rather than on him personally in the second
round of vote on Friday. (Russia-PM-Cabinet)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- An Iraqi girl who is suffering from cancer arrived in
Britain early Wednesday for medical treatment at a Scottish
children's hospital.
</P>
<P>
Four-year-old Mariam Hamza, whose plane touched down at
London's Heathrow airport Wednesday afternoon, would be
transferred to Glasgow's Royal Hospital for Sick Children in
Scotland for medical treatment.
</P>
<P>
Morgan Jameson, medical director of the Royal Hospital, told
BBC Radio, "The main thing will be to settle her down and get her
used to being here and to run a series of tests both to confirm
her diagnosis." (UK-Iraq-Girl Treatment) 
</P>
</TEXT>
