<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swiss Clears Transfer of Marcos Money to Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The Swiss Supreme Court has
cleared the way for the transfer to Manila of 540 million U.S.
dollars in Swiss bank accounts belonging to the late President
Ferdinand Marcos, Manila Standard reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Magtanggol Gunigundo, Chairman of the
Presidential Commission on Good Government, as saying that the
Swiss court last week dismissed the appeals of six Marcos
Foundations based in Panama and Liechtenstein.
</P>
<P>
The ruling paved the way for the release of the Marcos money to
an escrow account at the Philippine National Bank, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the Swiss court, the money could be released to
the Philippine government only if former First Lady Imelda Marcos
was convicted of guilty in a fair and final trial.
</P>
<P>
The court ordered the transfer to the Philippines of 100
million dollars of the Marcos deposits last December, then last
January it extended the ruling to cover the entire amount.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, a division of the Philippine Supreme Court
upheld a local court's ruling in 1993 which sentenced Imelda to 12
years of imprisonment. Imelda is appealing to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Imelda is running for the presidency in the coming
May elections. She suddenly announced on March 26 that her family
has at least 800 million U.S. dollars in Swiss bank accounts
besides the 540 million dollars to be returned to the Philippines.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
