<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> G-7 Appears to Support Japan's Fight to Defend Yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The Group of Seven industrial
countries agreed here Wednesday to cooperate in foreign exchange
markets and try to prevent excessive currency falls, urging Japan
to "quickly" take effective measures and structural reforms.
</P>
<P>
Financial leaders of the group said in a statement issued after
their meeting, which was attended by finance ministers and bank
governors from France, Britain, Canada, Italy, the U.S., Japan and
Germany, that Japan had taken positive steps to stimulate its
economy.
</P>
<P>
The yen depreciated sharply for the past months and reached its
lowest level in March against the dollar since early 1992, and the
International Monetary Fund projected Japan's economy growth in
1998 at zero.
</P>
<P>
The G-7 leaders believed that the measures announced by the
Japanese government last month would help correct the excessive
weakness of the yen.
</P>
<P>
"We emphasized that it is important to avoid excessive
depreciation where this could exacerbate large external
imbalances. In light of this, we support appropriate steps by
Japan aimed at stimulating domestic demand-led growth and reducing
external imbalances, thus also correcting the excessive
depreciation of the yen," they said.
</P>
<P>
However, the statement stressed, "The challenges facing Japan
are serious and have intensified in recent months."
</P>
<P>
"What is crucial (for Japan) is to implement quickly a strong
program of effective fiscal confidence," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Japan was the focus of the meeting, which is part of the spring
meetings of the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and the World
Bank. It will be followed up in England next month.
</P>
<P>
The statement noted that economic expansion remained strong in
North America and in Britain, while the growth in Germany, France
and Italy "gained momentum in 1997 and was expected to strengthen
further this year."
</P>
<P>
The G-7 financial leaders welcomed progress toward restoring
financial stability in crisis-wracked Asia and signs capital
markets were being restored in some countries in the region. They
urged Indonesia to implement "fully and vigorously" reforms.
</P>
<P>
But the ministers and bank governors indicated that
"substantial challenges" still faced the Asian nations and "there
is no time for complacency."
</P>
<P>
"A strong and enduring recovery requires a substantial
commitment to the macroeconomic and structural reform necessary to
restore confidence," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
The leaders said that they encouraged "emerging and transition
economies to pursue strong macroeconomic policies, improved
governance and structural reform programs to reduce their
vulnerability to contagion." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980416.0320 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
