<HEADLINE> Tobacco Excise Expected to Go up in New Zealand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The New Zealand government is
expected to charge 50 NZ cents (28 U.S. cents) more for each
packet of cigarettes from Nay to discourage smoking, the New
Zealand Press Association reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The price increase is expected in the government budget for
this year to be announced on May 14, which will contain a 50-cent
rise in Tobacco excise.
</P>
<P>
The report said the move has been pushed by the New Zealand
First party and will be the first one-off tobacco price increase
since the 1991 budget.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand First MP and Associate Treasurer Tuariki Delamere
has previously spoken publicly about the high level of
smoking-related diseases, and he is particularly concerned about
risks to young Maoris.
</P>
<P>
He is backed by some other Maori MPs in the New Zealand First
party, who have successfully urged Maori Affairs Minister Tau
Henare to quit smoking.
</P>
<P>
At present, a packet of 20 cigarettes sells at 6.15 NZ dollars
(about 3.5 U.S. dollars) or more, some 70 percent of which is
excise.
</P>
<P>
The government collects 650 million NZ dollars (358 million
U.S. dollars) a year in tobacco excise. An increase will bring in
another 50 million NZ dollars (about 27.7 million U.S. dollars) to
the government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
