<HEADLINE> New Zealand Succeeds in Cloning First Calf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, April 16 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand scientists have
developed the country's first cloned calf, the Wellington
newspaper "The Dominion" reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted scientist David Wells as telling a cloning
symposium in Melbourne, Australia, on Wednesday as saying that the
calf, named Jill, was developed by AgResearch scientists at a
research center near Hamilton in central North Island.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Wells said the technology could aid the New Zealand dairy
industry.
</P>
<P>
"Our aim is to develop the technology to the point where it can
provide commercial advantages for our agricultural industries,"
he stated.
</P>
<P>
Cloning could be used to develop herds for particular purposes,
 such as cows that produce specific kinds of milk.
</P>
<P>
In February last year, the research center produced two cloned
lambs, according to the report. 
</P>
