<BODY>
<HEADLINE> G-24 Developing Countries Urge Accelerated Debt Relief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The Group 24 developing
nations Wednesday urged the International Monetary Fund (IMF), the
World Bank and major industrial countries to accelerate the pace
of debt relief to countries undergoing economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
The G-24 developing countries also said in a communique that it
wants a task force of industrial and developing countries to
review the ability of these institutions to "prevent and to
respond in a timely and effective manner to crises induced by
large-scale capital movements."
</P>
<P>
The communique was issued after its 59th meeting concluded
Wednesday afternoon in Washington.
</P>
<P>
It said the G-24 would like to make more poor nations eligible
for the Heavily Indebted Poor Countries (HIPC) initiative which
was launched by the two international financial institutions in
September 1996, and to speed the disbursement of aid under the
international program.
</P>
<P>
Implementation of the HIPC initiative "is still slower than
expected," the communique noted.
</P>
<P>
HIPC is provided for low income debtor countries with a strong
record of reform with the most generous debt relief terms
creditors have ever offered. A group of 41 developing nations were
classified as being the heavily indebted poor countries, mainly in
the south-Saharan Africa.
</P>
<P>
So far, nearly 6 billion U.S. dollars in debt relief has been
offered to six countries. A week earlier, the IMF and the World
Bank approved a 2.9 billion dollar debt relief package for
war-torn Mozambique. They also completed a 650 million dollar
package for Uganda, making it the first recipient of debt relief
under the initiative. The Ivory Coast, Burkina Faso, Guyana and
Bolivia have also qualified.
</P>
<P>
G-24 ministers also voiced their support for promoting an
"orderly and gradual liberalization of capital movements."
</P>
<P>
These developing nations also called for a "cautious and
well-sequenced capital account liberalization," the communique
said.
</P>
<P>
China is not a member of the G-24, but was invited to attend
the group's ministerial meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
