<HEADLINE> G-7 Pledges to Prevent Currency Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The Group of Seven industrial
countries agreed here Wednesday to cooperate in foreign exchange
markets and try to prevent excessive currency falls.
</P>
<P>
Financial leaders of the group said in a communique issued
after their meeting that Japan has taken positive steps to
stimulate its economy.
</P>
<P>
They believed that the measures announced by the Japanese
government would help correct the excessive weakness of the yen.
</P>
<P>
"We emphasized that it is important to avoid excessive
depreciation where this could exacerbate large external
imbalances. In light of this, we support appropriate steps by
Japan aimed at stimulating domestic demand-led growth and reducing
external imbalances, thus also correcting the excessive
depreciation of the yen," they said.
</P>
<P>
Japan was the focus of the meeting which will be followed up in
England next month. The group comprises the United States,
Britain, Canada, France, Germany, Italy and Japan.
</P>
<P>
Japan, as the world's second largest economy, is facing
"serious challenges" which have intensified in recent months.
</P>
