<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Europe Slow in Bank Mergers, Newspaper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 15 (Xinhua) -- European banks are unlikely to
repeat the merging waves sweeping the U.S. banking sector,
although they are badly in need of consolidation, the Wall Street
Journal said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Cultural barriers, regulatory hurdles and national pride stand
in the way, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
To be sure, it said, European lenders worry about losing the
race to create truly global financial institutions, but, as the
pending merger of Union Bank of Switzerland and Swiss Bank Corp.
demonstrates, their sights remain set on home markets rather than
on pan-European combinations comparable to the agreed merger of
some U.S. banks.
</P>
<P>
The three mergers -- the BankAmerica deal as well as the
combinations between Banc One Corp. and First Chicago NBD Corp.,
and Travelers Group Inc. with Citicorp -- are worth more than 160
billion U.S. dollars. That is more than the value of all mergers
and acquisitions in the European financial sector combined in
1997. That figure was 134.1 billion dollars, in 463 deals, the
paper reported.
</P>
<P>
Not that European banks fail to recognize the need to
consolidate, it said. A common complaint among banks on the
Continent is that they have too many branches and too many
employees to achieve the sort of profit margins enjoyed by banks
in the U.S.
</P>
<P>
Now the more important task for European banking remains
cost-cutting, rather than revenue-enhancement. But even the
cost-cutting goal remains elusive in Europe, it said, given the
powerful sway that labor unions, governments, and public opinion
have over the industry.
</P>
<P>
However, it said, speculation continued that Credit Suisse
Group of Switzerland will be involved in the next major European
deal, with possible partners including some major German banks.
</P>
<P>
Other merger scenarios include Deutsche Bank AG with Munich
Re, Allianz AG with Dresdner Bank Ag, Barclays Bank PLC with
National Westminster Bank PLC, and HSBC Holdings PLC with J.P.
Morgan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
