<HEADLINE> Orange Order Says No to Northern Ireland Peace Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The Orange Order, a pro-British
Unionist group, decided Wednesday to reject the Northern Ireland
peace agreement reached last week.
</P>
<P>
After a meeting in Belfast, the Orange Order members agreed to
seek further clarification on key aspects of the peace deal,
including the future of Northern Ireland's police force and plans
for the release of prisoners belonging to guerrilla groups.
</P>
<P>
Grand Secretary John McCrea of the Orange Order was quoted by
the BBC television as saying that "certain vital issues" must be
clarified before the Unionist group could back the deal.
</P>
<P>
The "almost unanimous" no vote of the Orange Order, which has
25 percent control of the Ulster Unionist Council, could be
regarded a serious hurdle in achieving yes vote in the referendum
due to be held later next month in Northern Ireland. 
</P>
