<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Poll Sees Likely Power Change in Bonn </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 15 (Xinhua) -- An increasing number of German
political, economic and media elites now expect a power change in
Bonn after the country's general elections on September 27 this
year, a survey released Wednesday indicated.
</P>
<P>
According to the opinion poll conducted by the German Emnid
institute, about 49 percent of the questioned political, business
and media leaders said that the country's two main opposition
parties, the Social Democratic Party (SPD) and the Greens, would
form a ruling coalition after the elections.
</P>
<P>
At the beginning of this year, only 30 percent said they
expected such a power change in Bonn.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the survey also showed that only 23 percent still
believed that German Chancellor Helmut Kohl's current ruling
coalition -- his Christian Democratic Union (CDU), its Bavarian
sister party Christian Social Union (CSU) and the junior partner
Free Democratic Party (FDP) -- would remain in power after the
elections.
</P>
<P>
About 22 percent said it was more likely to see a grand
coalition between the CDU and the SPD.
</P>
<P>
Those who participated in the survey included government
officials, parliament members, business leaders and chief editors.
</P>
<P>
A majority of them said that CDU parliamentary leader Wolfgang
Schaeuble would have a better chance than Kohl to beat SPD
chancellor candidate Gerhard Schroeder in the September vote.
</P>
<P>
Most of them believed that unemployment would be the most
important issue for the election campaigns, followed by
crime-combating and reforms of the social welfare state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980416.0331 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Rising to Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Blue-chip stocks pushed farther
into record highs Wednesday as technology shares became more
active and set new record.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average twice surrendered gains of
more than 30 points, but turned higher again over the final hour,
finishing 52.07 points to 9,162.27 for its second straight record
close.
</P>
<P>
The technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index rose 20.23 to
1,863, easily topping its previous best finish of 1,855.40.
</P>
<P>
The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies also closed at a
record high, rising 2.27 to 487.12, beating April 2's mark of
486.43.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list rose 3.57 to 1,119.32,
moving within easy striking distance of April 3's record close of
1,122.70.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE composite index rose 1.46 to 582.77, less than a point
shy of the April 6 record of 583.17. The American Stock Exchange
composite index rose 2.60 to 742.46, about 5 points shy of record
terrain.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 10-to-9 margin on
the NYSE, with 1,569 up, 1,408 down and 551 unchanged. NYSE volume
totaled 677.23 million shares as of 4 p.m., vs. 611.43 million in
the previous session.
</P>
<P>
Intel and Compaq Computer stepped forward before the session
with tame profits for the first three months of the year. However,
both companies topped most estimates of Wall Street analysts.
</P>
<P>
Intel traded higher most of the day before finishing lower as
the most active Nasdaq issue. Compaq rose modestly as the most
active issue on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
IBM and Hewlett-Packard rose sharply as two of the Dow's
biggest gainers.
</P>
<P>
The Dow, which gained 97 points on Tuesday, has now gained
nearly 16 percent of the year, more than double what many analysts
had predicted for all of 1998.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
